1
00:00:06,326 --> 00:00:07,106
My name is Rich Wilson.

2
00:00:07,106 --> 00:00:09,468
I'm the level design lead at Arcane Austin.

3
00:00:09,468 --> 00:00:11,989
I'm here to talk about Mooncrash.

4
00:00:11,989 --> 00:00:16,431
More specifically, the talk is about questioning dogma.

5
00:00:16,431 --> 00:00:18,032
It's about sort of getting the opportunity

6
00:00:18,032 --> 00:00:21,574
to take something that you love and break it into pieces

7
00:00:21,574 --> 00:00:23,795
and then build something new with those pieces.

8
00:00:23,795 --> 00:00:31,700
And without further ado, there we go, all right.

9
00:00:31,700 --> 00:00:33,080
So the project,

10
00:00:33,582 --> 00:00:36,063
And this was a DLC for our core game, Prey,

11
00:00:36,063 --> 00:00:37,103
that we launched in 2017.

12
00:00:37,103 --> 00:00:40,304
So the project was defined by the dynamic tension

13
00:00:40,304 --> 00:00:43,244
between three major forces that we were dealing with.

14
00:00:43,244 --> 00:00:45,725
The motivation to do something different

15
00:00:45,725 --> 00:00:47,926
and a bit unorthodox to evolve our genre.

16
00:00:47,926 --> 00:00:50,646
The preservation of the studio and design team's

17
00:00:50,646 --> 00:00:54,147
core values, as well as testing ourselves

18
00:00:54,147 --> 00:00:56,568
to see which of those were worth keeping.

19
00:00:56,568 --> 00:00:58,908
And then adaptation to the new problems

20
00:00:58,908 --> 00:01:00,909
that we were going to get to solve

21
00:01:00,909 --> 00:01:02,889
as we incorporated all of the new ideas.

22
00:01:03,316 --> 00:01:06,557
given the direction change from Prey to Mooncrash.

23
00:01:06,557 --> 00:01:09,858
So to speak to that, a bit of a sort of digression,

24
00:01:09,858 --> 00:01:12,318
a quick summary of Prey and Mooncrash,

25
00:01:12,318 --> 00:01:13,999
just to make sure everyone's on the same page

26
00:01:13,999 --> 00:01:16,120
and kind of build a foundation.

27
00:01:16,120 --> 00:01:19,080
So Prey was an immersive simulation.

28
00:01:19,080 --> 00:01:23,622
It was kind of a hybrid first-person shooter RPG

29
00:01:23,622 --> 00:01:25,622
where you had basically alien abilities

30
00:01:25,622 --> 00:01:28,283
and science gadgets and tools and things like that

31
00:01:28,283 --> 00:01:29,723
to solve problems that came your way.

32
00:01:30,161 --> 00:01:31,442
So it wasn't just about shooting your way

33
00:01:31,442 --> 00:01:32,563
from point A to point B.

34
00:01:32,563 --> 00:01:33,904
There were guns, but they weren't

35
00:01:33,904 --> 00:01:35,445
the only way to solve problems.

36
00:01:35,445 --> 00:01:38,448
It was set in this confined,

37
00:01:38,448 --> 00:01:41,751
but fully explorable space station orbiting the moon.

38
00:01:41,751 --> 00:01:43,813
So you could travel anywhere within the station

39
00:01:43,813 --> 00:01:46,415
as well as without through zero-G travel

40
00:01:46,415 --> 00:01:47,756
and things like that.

41
00:01:47,756 --> 00:01:51,139
This design was inspired in part by games like System Shock

42
00:01:51,139 --> 00:01:53,961
and the studio's own history with games like Arx Fatalis,

43
00:01:53,961 --> 00:01:55,823
which was also inspired by Ultima Underworld.

44
00:01:56,474 --> 00:01:59,835
We use the term space dungeon colloquially within the studio

45
00:01:59,835 --> 00:02:01,776
to kind of express this idea.

46
00:02:01,776 --> 00:02:04,977
The objective is to escape the station.

47
00:02:04,977 --> 00:02:07,078
It's kind of a science fiction trope

48
00:02:07,078 --> 00:02:12,039
complete with this alien infestation of creatures called the Typhon.

49
00:02:12,039 --> 00:02:16,461
But we added wrinkles to that so it wasn't as tropey, I guess.

50
00:02:16,461 --> 00:02:18,802
So there's a psychological element to the game

51
00:02:18,802 --> 00:02:21,883
that makes the player kind of question their reality.

52
00:02:21,883 --> 00:02:23,443
You start the game in this fake apartment.

53
00:02:24,788 --> 00:02:27,169
And upon breaking your window to try to escape

54
00:02:27,169 --> 00:02:30,351
the apartment, you discover you're in this simulation,

55
00:02:30,351 --> 00:02:33,832
this sort of observational situation.

56
00:02:33,832 --> 00:02:34,792
And for the rest of the game,

57
00:02:34,792 --> 00:02:36,373
you're kind of unable to trust your eyes.

58
00:02:36,373 --> 00:02:39,354
There's a sort of pervasive sense of unease, basically,

59
00:02:39,354 --> 00:02:41,375
that permeates the game.

60
00:02:41,375 --> 00:02:44,916
There's also this looming moral framework to the game

61
00:02:44,916 --> 00:02:48,277
where you have to weigh the fates of everyone on the station

62
00:02:48,277 --> 00:02:50,798
against the people on Earth, against your own life.

63
00:02:50,798 --> 00:02:52,819
So it's this sort of immersive trolley problem.

64
00:02:53,163 --> 00:02:56,884
with the player's hand on the lever the whole game, basically.

65
00:02:56,884 --> 00:02:57,664
So next up is Mooncrash.

66
00:02:57,664 --> 00:03:02,066
This was a DLC, again, expansion for the main game.

67
00:03:02,066 --> 00:03:05,607
It's a mechanical extension of Prey,

68
00:03:05,607 --> 00:03:09,728
so it uses the same player mechanics as the core game.

69
00:03:09,728 --> 00:03:12,189
Weapons, abilities, things like that.

70
00:03:12,189 --> 00:03:15,890
First person, we didn't diverge too far in that regard.

71
00:03:17,159 --> 00:03:19,080
The story was adjacent to the main game.

72
00:03:19,080 --> 00:03:20,440
It wasn't really a prequel or a sequel.

73
00:03:20,440 --> 00:03:22,021
It happened kind of alongside.

74
00:03:22,021 --> 00:03:24,421
And it was set primarily within a simulation

75
00:03:24,421 --> 00:03:26,562
of a moon base owned by the same company

76
00:03:26,562 --> 00:03:29,523
that owned the space station from the original.

77
00:03:29,523 --> 00:03:31,704
But the simulation gave us a lot of wiggle room

78
00:03:31,704 --> 00:03:33,684
to play with the sort of meta structure of the game.

79
00:03:33,684 --> 00:03:37,085
And used a framing story for the narrative,

80
00:03:37,085 --> 00:03:38,886
the main narrative delivery,

81
00:03:38,886 --> 00:03:41,647
rather than moment to moment drama.

82
00:03:41,647 --> 00:03:43,267
You're a hacker diving into the simulation,

83
00:03:43,267 --> 00:03:44,528
so your story is separated

84
00:03:44,528 --> 00:03:46,768
from the moment to moment game, basically.

85
00:03:48,614 --> 00:03:50,915
One of the player's primary goals while in the simulation

86
00:03:50,915 --> 00:03:52,975
is to escape the moon base.

87
00:03:52,975 --> 00:03:55,036
And this is part of a list of player directed goals

88
00:03:55,036 --> 00:03:57,096
that took the place of Prey's series

89
00:03:57,096 --> 00:03:58,036
of story based objectives.

90
00:03:58,036 --> 00:04:00,417
And we'll talk more about this later as well.

91
00:04:00,417 --> 00:04:03,758
The game uses a roguelike framework,

92
00:04:03,758 --> 00:04:06,139
which means death is incorporated as part of the core loop.

93
00:04:06,139 --> 00:04:08,899
And there's a lot of variability between sessions,

94
00:04:08,899 --> 00:04:10,120
among other things.

95
00:04:10,120 --> 00:04:12,120
I'm gonna use roguelike for simplicity's sake.

96
00:04:12,120 --> 00:04:13,540
I know it's a very contested term,

97
00:04:13,540 --> 00:04:15,321
so don't add me on Twitter or anything.

98
00:04:18,256 --> 00:04:20,497
And a quick rundown on immersive sims as well,

99
00:04:20,497 --> 00:04:22,919
I know most of you are probably well versed,

100
00:04:22,919 --> 00:04:24,980
but again, it's a wide ranging subgenre,

101
00:04:24,980 --> 00:04:28,182
so kind of make sure everyone's on the same page.

102
00:04:28,182 --> 00:04:30,083
So immersive sims, they're a particular flavor

103
00:04:30,083 --> 00:04:32,504
of first person shooter, RPG hybrid,

104
00:04:32,504 --> 00:04:34,945
where we inject an extra level of simulation fidelity

105
00:04:34,945 --> 00:04:35,686
into the mix.

106
00:04:36,315 --> 00:04:40,458
So it's somewhere between the depth of Dwarf Fortress,

107
00:04:40,458 --> 00:04:44,501
and the immediacy and spatial inhabitation of Wolfenstein.

108
00:04:44,501 --> 00:04:49,404
So instead of a God's eye view and turn-based progression

109
00:04:49,404 --> 00:04:51,566
or whatever, you're actually inside the simulation,

110
00:04:51,566 --> 00:04:52,586
touching it with your hands.

111
00:04:52,586 --> 00:04:57,750
So this means there might be simulated fire propagation

112
00:04:57,750 --> 00:04:59,771
instead of fire just being a damaged volume

113
00:04:59,771 --> 00:05:01,072
with a particle effect attached.

114
00:05:01,741 --> 00:05:04,223
AI may have an organic awareness of the player

115
00:05:04,223 --> 00:05:06,404
and their surroundings, instead of magic knowledge

116
00:05:06,404 --> 00:05:08,847
of where the player is at all times.

117
00:05:08,847 --> 00:05:10,768
And so that's sort of what separates these

118
00:05:10,768 --> 00:05:19,816
from other first-person shooters.

119
00:05:19,816 --> 00:05:22,638
All right, so first up is the motivation section.

120
00:05:22,638 --> 00:05:26,041
This is our first step in the path to developing Mooncrash.

121
00:05:26,041 --> 00:05:28,143
And it's kind of set the tone for everything that followed.

122
00:05:29,347 --> 00:05:30,507
We took some creative risks,

123
00:05:30,507 --> 00:05:32,108
given the smaller scope of the project.

124
00:05:32,108 --> 00:05:33,148
We could have done something

125
00:05:33,148 --> 00:05:35,949
that was a standard story DLC extension.

126
00:05:35,949 --> 00:05:38,009
We could have followed the main antagonist

127
00:05:38,009 --> 00:05:39,829
from the core game, Commander Dahl,

128
00:05:39,829 --> 00:05:42,870
and did like we did with Knife of Dunwall and Dishonored.

129
00:05:42,870 --> 00:05:44,910
We could have even taken the moon base

130
00:05:44,910 --> 00:05:46,431
that we made the DLC out of

131
00:05:46,431 --> 00:05:51,812
and did a more story-based A to B kind of adventure there.

132
00:05:51,812 --> 00:05:53,892
So this section is about why we did not do that.

133
00:05:56,364 --> 00:05:59,126
So one reason was to grow outside of our domain.

134
00:05:59,126 --> 00:06:01,527
So when you go from project to project in AAA,

135
00:06:01,527 --> 00:06:02,908
a lot of the times you're solving

136
00:06:02,908 --> 00:06:05,809
the exact same problems every time

137
00:06:05,809 --> 00:06:08,210
with very little in the way of innovation.

138
00:06:08,210 --> 00:06:09,391
So are we gonna use lean this time?

139
00:06:09,391 --> 00:06:10,672
What are we mapping jump to?

140
00:06:10,672 --> 00:06:12,633
Are we using face buttons for the use?

141
00:06:12,633 --> 00:06:13,773
Stuff like that, right?

142
00:06:13,773 --> 00:06:17,155
This doesn't offer much in the way of creative growth.

143
00:06:17,155 --> 00:06:18,576
You're solving problems in the same domain

144
00:06:18,576 --> 00:06:19,937
and you're not getting to stretch your legs any.

145
00:06:20,769 --> 00:06:22,330
Sometimes this can even cause people to jump ship

146
00:06:22,330 --> 00:06:25,351
and go to other studios between projects

147
00:06:25,351 --> 00:06:26,651
and you're not really learning anything new.

148
00:06:26,651 --> 00:06:28,612
So with Mooncrash, this meant a kind of

149
00:06:28,612 --> 00:06:30,572
a cross-genre exploration.

150
00:06:30,572 --> 00:06:33,653
We explored some ideas for random level elements in Prey

151
00:06:33,653 --> 00:06:35,574
that ended up getting cut for Scope.

152
00:06:35,574 --> 00:06:38,055
So we took that and leaned more heavily into that

153
00:06:38,055 --> 00:06:40,395
and brought some of that stuff back

154
00:06:40,395 --> 00:06:42,056
and more roguelike elements on board

155
00:06:42,056 --> 00:06:45,777
because it seemed like a natural extension of those ideas.

156
00:06:45,777 --> 00:06:46,677
So once we made that decision,

157
00:06:46,677 --> 00:06:48,698
then we could look into the roguelike space.

158
00:06:49,058 --> 00:06:50,859
and look at their problems and their solutions

159
00:06:50,859 --> 00:06:55,360
and things like that and learn from them basically.

160
00:06:55,360 --> 00:06:58,020
Issues like respawning and persistence,

161
00:06:58,020 --> 00:07:00,401
difficulty escalation, character variety.

162
00:07:00,401 --> 00:07:03,041
So games like Spelunky, Rogue Legacy and Risk of Rain,

163
00:07:03,041 --> 00:07:04,422
they were basically master classes

164
00:07:04,422 --> 00:07:05,962
in these other spheres of thought

165
00:07:05,962 --> 00:07:07,682
that we hadn't really explored yet.

166
00:07:07,682 --> 00:07:12,443
And so why did we pick the roguelike genre specifically?

167
00:07:12,443 --> 00:07:14,064
Part of it was design team bias.

168
00:07:14,064 --> 00:07:16,104
A lot of us were playing some of these games at the time.

169
00:07:16,104 --> 00:07:18,165
Risk of Rain, Darkest Dungeon, things like that.

170
00:07:18,835 --> 00:07:21,717
A big part of it also is the kinship between the genres.

171
00:07:21,717 --> 00:07:23,639
So roguelikes generally rely heavily

172
00:07:23,639 --> 00:07:26,401
on a player's internalization of systems.

173
00:07:26,401 --> 00:07:28,022
They don't rely on rote memorization

174
00:07:28,022 --> 00:07:30,563
and they generally allow for expressive players

175
00:07:30,563 --> 00:07:32,485
and emergent situations.

176
00:07:32,485 --> 00:07:35,287
And a lot of those core values really speak

177
00:07:35,287 --> 00:07:36,668
to what we do in Immersive Sims as well.

178
00:07:36,668 --> 00:07:38,169
So there was a lot of overlap there.

179
00:07:38,169 --> 00:07:42,311
So another thing we wanted to do

180
00:07:42,311 --> 00:07:45,313
was sort of deconstruct our genre.

181
00:07:45,855 --> 00:07:48,657
So searching for these new problems to solve,

182
00:07:48,657 --> 00:07:51,119
it afforded us the opportunity to deconstruct our games

183
00:07:51,119 --> 00:07:54,221
and basically take the constituent parts

184
00:07:54,221 --> 00:07:56,583
and spread them all out and kind of evaluate them

185
00:07:56,583 --> 00:07:57,303
individually, right?

186
00:07:57,303 --> 00:07:59,845
You know, we take for granted that the player

187
00:07:59,845 --> 00:08:01,947
can hack keypads or crawl through events

188
00:08:01,947 --> 00:08:03,508
or things like that.

189
00:08:03,508 --> 00:08:06,029
So isolating these parts and then recontextualizing them

190
00:08:06,029 --> 00:08:08,531
and looking at them in a new light means

191
00:08:08,531 --> 00:08:10,713
we could ask ourselves why we use them

192
00:08:10,713 --> 00:08:12,774
and why we adopted them in the first place.

193
00:08:12,774 --> 00:08:13,435
It's like moving,

194
00:08:13,892 --> 00:08:16,453
between houses and then you have this dog clock

195
00:08:16,453 --> 00:08:18,214
that your grandmother gave you and you can finally

196
00:08:18,214 --> 00:08:20,755
ask yourself why are you holding onto this thing.

197
00:08:20,755 --> 00:08:23,315
It's a win in either case because you either get rid

198
00:08:23,315 --> 00:08:25,916
of baggage or you remind yourself why this thing

199
00:08:25,916 --> 00:08:27,937
was important to you and you keep it and take it along.

200
00:08:27,937 --> 00:08:32,038
Some examples from Mooncrash, character skill trees

201
00:08:32,038 --> 00:08:34,459
for instance, this was something we had on the block

202
00:08:34,459 --> 00:08:37,160
and we're looking at and we decided to keep it

203
00:08:37,160 --> 00:08:39,001
and brought it over to Mooncrash.

204
00:08:39,001 --> 00:08:41,302
A linear sort of beat by beat narrative.

205
00:08:41,733 --> 00:08:43,474
That was something we examined and decided

206
00:08:43,474 --> 00:08:47,017
did not belong in the DLC, so we set it aside.

207
00:08:47,017 --> 00:08:54,683
Another motivating factor was DLC being

208
00:08:54,683 --> 00:08:57,065
this sort of stable launch pad.

209
00:08:57,065 --> 00:08:59,848
One of the cool things about a DLC project

210
00:08:59,848 --> 00:09:02,410
is that usually you're starting with this really extensive

211
00:09:02,410 --> 00:09:05,052
and refined tool set from the previous project.

212
00:09:05,052 --> 00:09:08,375
And you've got studio expertise, assets,

213
00:09:08,375 --> 00:09:09,696
and the ability to prototype things

214
00:09:09,696 --> 00:09:11,437
really rapidly and extensively.

215
00:09:11,968 --> 00:09:14,110
Your metrics and mechanics are also in place.

216
00:09:14,110 --> 00:09:17,333
This is something you can't really take for granted

217
00:09:17,333 --> 00:09:18,634
because it's very valuable.

218
00:09:18,634 --> 00:09:21,656
So even if you're planning to diverge a bit,

219
00:09:21,656 --> 00:09:23,838
this starting point can really be immense

220
00:09:23,838 --> 00:09:26,900
for prototyping and getting started.

221
00:09:26,900 --> 00:09:29,762
These sort of pre-existing assets and engine

222
00:09:29,762 --> 00:09:32,124
and things like that act like a force multiplier

223
00:09:32,124 --> 00:09:34,866
for small teams, and DLC are usually small teams.

224
00:09:34,866 --> 00:09:37,268
So as a motivating factor, again,

225
00:09:37,268 --> 00:09:40,611
this kind of leverage encourages us to kind of flex a bit

226
00:09:40,611 --> 00:09:41,552
and try something.

227
00:09:42,432 --> 00:09:46,253
A good example of this as well is we had a game jam

228
00:09:46,253 --> 00:09:48,494
in between the main game and the DLC.

229
00:09:48,494 --> 00:09:52,855
One purpose of this was to help the team blow off steam

230
00:09:52,855 --> 00:09:56,196
as people ramped off of the project and onto other things,

231
00:09:56,196 --> 00:10:00,557
or onto the next project, but another thing this served

232
00:10:00,557 --> 00:10:03,178
was as an incubator for ideas for the DLC.

233
00:10:03,178 --> 00:10:07,339
So we had things like VFX laden basketball games

234
00:10:07,339 --> 00:10:10,860
complete with scoring mechanisms and jump pads.

235
00:10:11,126 --> 00:10:14,427
We had this dance party involving the Typhon organisms.

236
00:10:14,427 --> 00:10:17,608
We even had some things that made it into the DLC,

237
00:10:17,608 --> 00:10:21,469
like the tentacle grenade here and the mimic companions.

238
00:10:21,469 --> 00:10:24,230
Both of those things actually made it fully into the DLC.

239
00:10:24,230 --> 00:10:27,251
A lot of the content wasn't ultimately used

240
00:10:27,251 --> 00:10:28,011
for anything that shipped,

241
00:10:28,011 --> 00:10:29,491
but the exercise was really valuable.

242
00:10:29,491 --> 00:10:30,792
A lot of the team members,

243
00:10:30,792 --> 00:10:32,112
they got to play with development tools

244
00:10:32,112 --> 00:10:33,112
they wouldn't normally use.

245
00:10:33,112 --> 00:10:36,453
They got to kind of step outside of their box for a bit.

246
00:10:36,854 --> 00:10:39,877
And it also helped motivate the team to try new things.

247
00:10:39,877 --> 00:10:44,401
It was sort of engendering this spirit of exploration.

248
00:10:44,401 --> 00:10:52,908
All right, so preserving what we do best

249
00:10:52,908 --> 00:10:54,490
and what we love about Immersive Sims

250
00:10:54,490 --> 00:10:55,851
was a big part of this project.

251
00:10:55,851 --> 00:10:57,913
It was a big deal because on other projects,

252
00:10:57,913 --> 00:11:00,535
these values generally just tag along as a matter of course.

253
00:11:00,535 --> 00:11:01,897
They're just something we take for granted.

254
00:11:02,993 --> 00:11:05,675
But in this project, we were explicitly calling

255
00:11:05,675 --> 00:11:09,817
these things into question and sort of explicitly

256
00:11:09,817 --> 00:11:12,619
bringing these values along,

257
00:11:12,619 --> 00:11:14,460
the ones we thought worked and such.

258
00:11:14,460 --> 00:11:17,621
We also didn't want to lose sight of what worked for us

259
00:11:17,621 --> 00:11:18,702
in pursuit of something new,

260
00:11:18,702 --> 00:11:19,623
but we didn't want to cling too tightly

261
00:11:19,623 --> 00:11:20,343
to dogma out of blind habit.

262
00:11:20,343 --> 00:11:23,645
So there wasn't like a clean deconstruction phase

263
00:11:23,645 --> 00:11:25,826
that preceded actual development,

264
00:11:25,826 --> 00:11:27,187
but as we pared things down in meetings,

265
00:11:27,187 --> 00:11:28,567
we gradually got a more focused picture

266
00:11:28,567 --> 00:11:31,509
of the values that we wanted to preserve as we move forward.

267
00:11:33,543 --> 00:11:34,664
So one worry early on was,

268
00:11:34,664 --> 00:11:37,005
especially from the design department,

269
00:11:37,005 --> 00:11:38,486
was that moving to a roguelike model

270
00:11:38,486 --> 00:11:41,588
would mean we were completely tossing Arkane's knack

271
00:11:41,588 --> 00:11:43,789
for world building and environmental storytelling

272
00:11:43,789 --> 00:11:44,429
out the window.

273
00:11:44,429 --> 00:11:48,251
But this was one of the dogmas that we wanted to hang on to

274
00:11:48,251 --> 00:11:50,172
and because we explicitly sort of analyzed it

275
00:11:50,172 --> 00:11:51,213
and decided we wanted it,

276
00:11:51,213 --> 00:11:53,294
not just because it was something we always do.

277
00:11:53,294 --> 00:11:56,336
So this survived the transition,

278
00:11:56,336 --> 00:11:57,456
remarkably intact actually.

279
00:11:57,456 --> 00:12:00,578
A large part of this is because Arkane's emphasis

280
00:12:00,578 --> 00:12:01,678
is usually on player story.

281
00:12:02,389 --> 00:12:04,350
So the bulk of our storytelling work also happens

282
00:12:04,350 --> 00:12:06,912
in the environment, like a lot of our prescriptive stories,

283
00:12:06,912 --> 00:12:08,433
environmental stuff.

284
00:12:08,433 --> 00:12:10,934
And this worked really well with Mooncrash,

285
00:12:10,934 --> 00:12:13,416
because the game takes place in a defined fictional location

286
00:12:13,416 --> 00:12:16,337
and the main character's job was to find out

287
00:12:16,337 --> 00:12:18,699
what happened there, and so that pairs very well

288
00:12:18,699 --> 00:12:20,279
with environmental storytelling.

289
00:12:20,279 --> 00:12:26,803
So speaking of values, quite a while back,

290
00:12:26,803 --> 00:12:29,205
Chris Crawford, he coined the term process intensity.

291
00:12:29,774 --> 00:12:32,376
in describing what computers are better suited for

292
00:12:32,376 --> 00:12:33,377
versus what they aren't.

293
00:12:33,377 --> 00:12:35,778
And you can see him here at GDC92,

294
00:12:35,778 --> 00:12:39,140
brandishing a sword as you do.

295
00:12:39,140 --> 00:12:42,302
And this is what he said on the subject of process intensity.

296
00:12:42,302 --> 00:12:44,224
I'll drink water while people read.

297
00:12:44,224 --> 00:12:48,827
So the short version is that processors are more useful

298
00:12:48,827 --> 00:12:52,609
with game systems than they are with game content.

299
00:12:52,609 --> 00:12:56,712
They're more useful with verbs than they are with nouns.

300
00:12:57,152 --> 00:13:01,497
And this is what games can flaunt that other media can't, basically.

301
00:13:01,497 --> 00:13:05,882
So immersive sims embody this concept pretty well, pretty heavily.

302
00:13:05,882 --> 00:13:09,666
They pull content towards the process end of the spectrum, basically.

303
00:13:09,666 --> 00:13:14,231
And we leveraged this more extensively in Mooncrash than we even did in Prey.

304
00:13:14,231 --> 00:13:16,293
Part of this was a question of economics.

305
00:13:16,929 --> 00:13:19,170
So if you look at more process intensive games,

306
00:13:19,170 --> 00:13:20,771
they've got a much higher consumption time

307
00:13:20,771 --> 00:13:21,632
to development time ratio.

308
00:13:21,632 --> 00:13:24,753
If you look at something like Counter-Strike or Quake,

309
00:13:24,753 --> 00:13:27,394
for instance, the footprint of one of those levels,

310
00:13:27,394 --> 00:13:30,436
you get a lot more hours of gameplay out of one of those

311
00:13:30,436 --> 00:13:34,878
than a more linear narrative kind of game.

312
00:13:34,878 --> 00:13:38,320
Consumption time's not a be all, end all of games.

313
00:13:38,320 --> 00:13:41,201
I'm not preaching that by any means.

314
00:13:41,201 --> 00:13:43,263
But I'm mainly talking about development economics

315
00:13:43,263 --> 00:13:43,803
and how

316
00:13:44,682 --> 00:13:46,103
we were able to leverage that.

317
00:13:46,103 --> 00:13:47,964
There's a whole spectrum of experiences

318
00:13:47,964 --> 00:13:50,405
on the sort of process to content continuum,

319
00:13:50,405 --> 00:13:50,925
and that's fine.

320
00:13:50,925 --> 00:13:57,208
Now process-intense games also respond more dynamically

321
00:13:57,208 --> 00:14:00,250
to player choice, which is a boon for agency,

322
00:14:00,250 --> 00:14:01,971
you know, the player's sense of having an impact

323
00:14:01,971 --> 00:14:02,451
on the game world.

324
00:14:02,451 --> 00:14:05,432
There are multiple tiers of agency,

325
00:14:05,432 --> 00:14:07,473
and again, this is kind of a recap of Design 101,

326
00:14:07,473 --> 00:14:10,355
but low-level agency is stuff like footstep sounds,

327
00:14:10,355 --> 00:14:11,635
bullet impact effects, you know,

328
00:14:11,635 --> 00:14:13,236
the enemy's reacting to your presence.

329
00:14:13,589 --> 00:14:16,750
sort of base level acknowledgement of your existence at all.

330
00:14:16,750 --> 00:14:19,951
Then you've got high level agency,

331
00:14:19,951 --> 00:14:22,672
which is more narrative impact kind of stuff.

332
00:14:22,672 --> 00:14:25,393
Dialogue options based off of the fates of characters

333
00:14:25,393 --> 00:14:26,734
or different endings to the game.

334
00:14:26,734 --> 00:14:29,775
The lower level agency stuff is much more process intense,

335
00:14:29,775 --> 00:14:32,075
while the higher level stuff gets simpler and simpler

336
00:14:32,075 --> 00:14:35,196
on the process end, and more intense on the content end.

337
00:14:35,196 --> 00:14:38,698
So the fate of the world can just be like a Boolean flag

338
00:14:38,698 --> 00:14:41,679
or an integer index that's checked by one script node

339
00:14:41,679 --> 00:14:42,479
at the end.

340
00:14:43,407 --> 00:14:45,429
on the content and you're gonna have to author

341
00:14:45,429 --> 00:14:47,530
four different cut scenes with voice acting

342
00:14:47,530 --> 00:14:49,392
and things like that, right?

343
00:14:49,392 --> 00:14:51,393
So in Mooncrash we didn't retain Prey's sense

344
00:14:51,393 --> 00:14:52,634
of higher level player agency.

345
00:14:52,634 --> 00:14:55,296
That was something we set aside.

346
00:14:55,296 --> 00:14:56,937
You can't really affect the ending of the game.

347
00:14:56,937 --> 00:14:59,299
There aren't any conditional blocks of dialogue

348
00:14:59,299 --> 00:15:01,581
based on your actions or anything like that.

349
00:15:01,581 --> 00:15:03,862
Because monolithic moment to moment story

350
00:15:03,862 --> 00:15:06,204
doesn't play as big a role in that game.

351
00:15:06,204 --> 00:15:08,306
It was all intentional.

352
00:15:08,306 --> 00:15:09,687
What we did double down on, however,

353
00:15:09,687 --> 00:15:11,248
was the lower level agency

354
00:15:11,248 --> 00:15:12,869
and a sort of sense of intentionality.

355
00:15:13,408 --> 00:15:14,148
in the player.

356
00:15:14,148 --> 00:15:21,094
So, again, speaking of sort of core values, right?

357
00:15:21,094 --> 00:15:23,496
As I mentioned earlier, one handy overlap

358
00:15:23,496 --> 00:15:26,158
between roguelikes and immersive sims,

359
00:15:26,158 --> 00:15:27,519
and one of our core values,

360
00:15:27,519 --> 00:15:30,342
our core values are a bias towards systems.

361
00:15:30,342 --> 00:15:33,064
So the drama and gameplay with both

362
00:15:33,064 --> 00:15:35,286
generally relies on novel situations

363
00:15:35,286 --> 00:15:37,587
emerging from the interactions of systems,

364
00:15:37,587 --> 00:15:39,169
rather than hand-scripted cinematic scenes.

365
00:15:39,169 --> 00:15:41,931
You know, the player's story is paramount in these games.

366
00:15:42,410 --> 00:15:45,113
So a quick example of systemic design,

367
00:15:45,113 --> 00:15:46,114
and again this is kind of 101.

368
00:15:46,114 --> 00:15:48,076
So let's say there's an ice wall in the game

369
00:15:48,076 --> 00:15:50,359
blocking the player's path and the player has to get past it

370
00:15:50,359 --> 00:15:53,142
to progress through the game, right?

371
00:15:53,142 --> 00:15:56,466
The, there we go, the non-systemic approach

372
00:15:56,466 --> 00:15:58,589
might be to have a variable that's tied to the player

373
00:15:58,589 --> 00:16:00,291
picking up a specific item in the game.

374
00:16:00,782 --> 00:16:02,544
and then there's a trigger in front of the wall,

375
00:16:02,544 --> 00:16:05,146
and when the player enters that trigger,

376
00:16:05,146 --> 00:16:08,028
it checks that value, says yes or no or whatever,

377
00:16:08,028 --> 00:16:11,872
plays some VFX, Steam, plays an animation

378
00:16:11,872 --> 00:16:13,653
as the ice melts away, things like that, right?

379
00:16:13,653 --> 00:16:16,896
This is really rigid, it's a rigid relationship,

380
00:16:16,896 --> 00:16:19,078
there's a very lock and key kind of thing going on here,

381
00:16:19,078 --> 00:16:21,540
they're not very flexible.

382
00:16:21,540 --> 00:16:26,344
So in immersive sims, you start with the concept of heat.

383
00:16:26,819 --> 00:16:31,842
This abstract concept, heat is a signal that can be

384
00:16:31,842 --> 00:16:33,122
passed between objects.

385
00:16:33,122 --> 00:16:36,144
And in that case, anything in the world can emit

386
00:16:36,144 --> 00:16:37,985
and respond to heat, and so we say, okay,

387
00:16:37,985 --> 00:16:39,545
the torch is a thing that emits heat.

388
00:16:39,545 --> 00:16:43,507
The wall is something that can respond to heat.

389
00:16:43,507 --> 00:16:45,488
And so now, when you get close to the ice wall

390
00:16:45,488 --> 00:16:48,270
with the torch, you can say, okay,

391
00:16:48,270 --> 00:16:50,411
the ice wall responds to that by melting.

392
00:16:50,411 --> 00:16:51,911
You can do the same animation in VFX,

393
00:16:51,911 --> 00:16:53,752
as in the non-systemic version.

394
00:16:55,161 --> 00:16:57,162
But now you've got these systems that can more dynamically

395
00:16:57,162 --> 00:16:59,945
play off of one another and potentially produce novel

396
00:16:59,945 --> 00:17:02,847
and player-driven results and provide plenty

397
00:17:02,847 --> 00:17:07,090
of novel scenarios for the QA department in the process.

398
00:17:07,090 --> 00:17:10,413
So when I say player-driven, this means the player's

399
00:17:10,413 --> 00:17:12,674
conceiving of ways to solve the problem

400
00:17:12,674 --> 00:17:14,776
rather than reading the designer's mind.

401
00:17:14,776 --> 00:17:16,937
And that's kind of key to our, again, our values,

402
00:17:16,937 --> 00:17:18,979
the things we want to preserve between projects.

403
00:17:19,778 --> 00:17:21,820
This also means that in most immersive sims,

404
00:17:21,820 --> 00:17:24,221
the torch won't be the only way to bypass the blockage.

405
00:17:24,221 --> 00:17:27,483
There's no real point in having a novel simulation-based

406
00:17:27,483 --> 00:17:30,645
system if you're only gonna have one way to solve a problem.

407
00:17:30,645 --> 00:17:33,247
But now that you've got heat,

408
00:17:33,247 --> 00:17:36,589
now that anything in the world can generate heat,

409
00:17:36,589 --> 00:17:38,190
you can have any kind of heat sources.

410
00:17:38,190 --> 00:17:41,372
You can have a barrel explode next to the wall and melt it.

411
00:17:42,017 --> 00:17:46,459
You can have a dragon that breathes fire at you and you dodge out of the way.

412
00:17:46,459 --> 00:17:51,340
You can have Channing Tatum dance next to the wall and melt it.

413
00:17:51,340 --> 00:17:54,581
So any kind of thing you want that generates heat.

414
00:17:54,581 --> 00:17:59,743
Also this means the torch can also go and live a life of its own as a generic heat source

415
00:17:59,743 --> 00:18:03,344
so it can cook food items, it can spread through grass, it can burn enemies, etc.

416
00:18:12,607 --> 00:18:14,747
So systemic design ties back into agency

417
00:18:14,747 --> 00:18:18,068
because a player with an expressive set of tools like this

418
00:18:18,068 --> 00:18:19,669
in a consistently responsive world

419
00:18:19,669 --> 00:18:21,149
can genuinely have an impact on that world.

420
00:18:21,149 --> 00:18:23,230
The consistent rules give the player

421
00:18:23,230 --> 00:18:24,290
a sense of intentionality,

422
00:18:24,290 --> 00:18:27,411
and so that means they can make informed decisions.

423
00:18:27,411 --> 00:18:28,871
And the emergent nature of the game

424
00:18:28,871 --> 00:18:32,272
can provide surprises and novel results

425
00:18:32,272 --> 00:18:33,733
so things don't get too stale or predictable,

426
00:18:33,733 --> 00:18:35,753
and it's kind of a balancing act, right?

427
00:18:35,753 --> 00:18:38,154
Like making sure things are interesting enough

428
00:18:38,154 --> 00:18:40,275
but also predictable enough,

429
00:18:40,275 --> 00:18:42,315
and you have to have kind of found the sweet spot there.

430
00:18:45,563 --> 00:18:48,266
So one example of systemic design in Mooncrash

431
00:18:48,266 --> 00:18:51,428
is the player learns there are these devices

432
00:18:51,428 --> 00:18:53,590
called Typhon gates, and they block your passage

433
00:18:53,590 --> 00:18:54,611
if there are enemies nearby.

434
00:18:54,611 --> 00:18:56,973
So you can see the gate there,

435
00:18:56,973 --> 00:18:59,455
and it tracks how many enemies are close and all that stuff.

436
00:18:59,455 --> 00:19:03,418
There's an enemy called the Moonshark

437
00:19:03,418 --> 00:19:05,780
that patrols and levels underground.

438
00:19:05,780 --> 00:19:08,402
It's blind, so it chases whatever vibrations

439
00:19:08,402 --> 00:19:09,663
it can sense in the soil.

440
00:19:09,663 --> 00:19:12,385
And it's also massive and really hard to kill,

441
00:19:12,385 --> 00:19:14,087
so the player is disinclined.

442
00:19:14,687 --> 00:19:15,748
from engaging with the thing.

443
00:19:15,748 --> 00:19:18,189
So we wanna avoid confrontations,

444
00:19:18,189 --> 00:19:21,450
especially in the beginning when the player's weak.

445
00:19:21,450 --> 00:19:24,252
So you have a situation where the Moonshark

446
00:19:24,252 --> 00:19:25,332
is near the Typhon Gate,

447
00:19:25,332 --> 00:19:27,413
and how does the player get past the gate, right?

448
00:19:27,413 --> 00:19:30,574
So the player can put all of these kind of elements together

449
00:19:30,574 --> 00:19:33,516
and decide, okay, I'll throw a projectile really far away.

450
00:19:33,516 --> 00:19:35,537
The Moonshark will sense that, it will go chase it.

451
00:19:35,537 --> 00:19:39,378
The Typhon Gate will drop, I get to pass through.

452
00:19:39,378 --> 00:19:40,999
And that was all the player's sort of,

453
00:19:41,547 --> 00:19:44,190
generation of the idea, not us saying,

454
00:19:44,190 --> 00:19:45,891
well this is exactly what you have to do.

455
00:19:45,891 --> 00:19:47,253
We'll tutorialize it and we'll step you

456
00:19:47,253 --> 00:19:48,334
through all the processes, right?

457
00:19:48,334 --> 00:19:50,756
This was sort of a bottom-up kind of solution

458
00:19:50,756 --> 00:19:51,517
on the player's part.

459
00:19:51,517 --> 00:19:54,219
One metric we use for game objects at Arkane

460
00:19:54,219 --> 00:19:56,201
is how many systems interact with them.

461
00:19:56,201 --> 00:19:57,622
So the Typhon gates, for instance,

462
00:19:57,622 --> 00:20:01,466
interact with the AI ecosystem, like in the example here.

463
00:20:01,466 --> 00:20:03,067
But they also interact with player progression.

464
00:20:03,067 --> 00:20:04,269
So if you get too many alien upgrades,

465
00:20:04,269 --> 00:20:07,392
the things will actually lock down when you're nearby.

466
00:20:07,964 --> 00:20:10,086
They interact with the EMP system,

467
00:20:10,086 --> 00:20:13,248
so much like the heat stimulus that I mentioned earlier,

468
00:20:13,248 --> 00:20:14,729
EMP is also a stimulus in our game,

469
00:20:14,729 --> 00:20:17,391
so you can use any kind of like stun guns

470
00:20:17,391 --> 00:20:18,852
or exploding batteries or things like that

471
00:20:18,852 --> 00:20:20,494
to take them down.

472
00:20:20,494 --> 00:20:22,215
Player powers also interact with these things,

473
00:20:22,215 --> 00:20:23,576
so the player can burrow beneath

474
00:20:23,576 --> 00:20:25,758
or use an EMP power as well.

475
00:20:25,758 --> 00:20:28,500
And this is similar to the thought processes

476
00:20:28,500 --> 00:20:29,601
behind things like the walls of light

477
00:20:29,601 --> 00:20:30,982
and Dishonored and so forth.

478
00:20:32,706 --> 00:20:35,207
But it may look at first like there are a thousand

479
00:20:35,207 --> 00:20:37,147
different ways to get around these things.

480
00:20:37,147 --> 00:20:38,688
But the truth is, in the beginning,

481
00:20:38,688 --> 00:20:40,888
the player only has a handful of these tools,

482
00:20:40,888 --> 00:20:42,949
like one, maybe two tops in the beginning.

483
00:20:42,949 --> 00:20:46,130
And then as they gradually progress over the game,

484
00:20:46,130 --> 00:20:48,610
they get more and more tools to get past the things.

485
00:20:48,610 --> 00:20:50,791
So there's this sort of organic process

486
00:20:50,791 --> 00:20:53,292
where by the time the player would be getting frustrated

487
00:20:53,292 --> 00:20:54,652
and tired of dealing with Typhon gates,

488
00:20:54,652 --> 00:20:56,172
they have all these expressive tools

489
00:20:56,172 --> 00:20:57,913
to get past Typhon gates.

490
00:20:57,913 --> 00:20:59,233
And so it's a problem that kind of actually

491
00:20:59,233 --> 00:21:00,574
takes care of itself over time,

492
00:21:00,574 --> 00:21:02,134
and it's this interesting relationship.

493
00:21:06,338 --> 00:21:08,659
So why do we make these things?

494
00:21:08,659 --> 00:21:11,760
Again, looking at our values, looking at moving forward,

495
00:21:11,760 --> 00:21:14,401
why do we want to keep this stuff around?

496
00:21:14,401 --> 00:21:16,222
Immersive sims can be a sea of chaos.

497
00:21:16,222 --> 00:21:18,543
Systems interact in unpredictable ways.

498
00:21:18,543 --> 00:21:20,824
Organic AI awareness means you can put a basket

499
00:21:20,824 --> 00:21:23,125
over someone's head and then rob them blind.

500
00:21:23,125 --> 00:21:25,065
If you get too close to a quest giver

501
00:21:25,065 --> 00:21:26,286
and you have a torch and they have a broom,

502
00:21:26,286 --> 00:21:27,707
maybe their broom catches on fire

503
00:21:27,707 --> 00:21:29,867
and then they freak out and attack you

504
00:21:29,867 --> 00:21:30,808
or something like that, right?

505
00:21:31,242 --> 00:21:34,063
You go to pick up a key card and you kick it into a lake,

506
00:21:34,063 --> 00:21:35,503
tons of things, right?

507
00:21:35,503 --> 00:21:37,864
But when you have this terrarium of systems

508
00:21:37,864 --> 00:21:40,284
that interact in these internally consistent ways,

509
00:21:40,284 --> 00:21:42,625
these things begin to take on a life of their own.

510
00:21:42,625 --> 00:21:45,266
Instead of depicting something that happened to a player,

511
00:21:45,266 --> 00:21:47,766
you're actually building a microcosmic reality.

512
00:21:47,766 --> 00:21:50,867
And the players that these games attract

513
00:21:50,867 --> 00:21:51,987
end up falling in love with them

514
00:21:51,987 --> 00:21:53,428
because of that sort of internally,

515
00:21:53,428 --> 00:21:56,488
I don't know, the sort of small world you're building.

516
00:22:05,839 --> 00:22:07,960
So a large part of Mooncrash was taking these new mechanics,

517
00:22:07,960 --> 00:22:11,522
these sort of roguelike ideas and things like that,

518
00:22:11,522 --> 00:22:14,224
and adapting everything to this hybrid

519
00:22:14,224 --> 00:22:15,245
that we were creating.

520
00:22:15,245 --> 00:22:17,286
A lot of things we took for granted,

521
00:22:17,286 --> 00:22:20,288
we now had to figure out how to work with new ideas.

522
00:22:20,288 --> 00:22:24,510
So one of the big things were playable characters.

523
00:22:24,510 --> 00:22:26,451
And this is one of the systems

524
00:22:26,451 --> 00:22:28,132
we debated most on the project.

525
00:22:28,636 --> 00:22:30,817
Some versions we had one playable character

526
00:22:30,817 --> 00:22:34,519
we were gonna have that could be retooled in a lot of ways.

527
00:22:34,519 --> 00:22:36,219
Some versions on the drawing board,

528
00:22:36,219 --> 00:22:37,840
we had dozens of variants in the character

529
00:22:37,840 --> 00:22:40,621
that were, there was no real narrative veneer to them.

530
00:22:40,621 --> 00:22:43,162
They were just kind of buckets of mechanics.

531
00:22:43,162 --> 00:22:45,243
And we settled on what I think ended up working best

532
00:22:45,243 --> 00:22:46,484
for our game and our studio.

533
00:22:46,484 --> 00:22:48,145
The characters had names and faces,

534
00:22:48,145 --> 00:22:50,666
they had personalities and backstories.

535
00:22:50,666 --> 00:22:51,466
And this worked really well

536
00:22:51,466 --> 00:22:52,687
with our traditional storytelling methods.

537
00:22:52,687 --> 00:22:54,267
We could put a lot into the backstory

538
00:22:54,267 --> 00:22:56,168
and then let the abilities kind of speak

539
00:22:56,168 --> 00:22:57,189
for the characters, right?

540
00:22:57,189 --> 00:22:58,369
And let the player speak through that.

541
00:22:59,219 --> 00:23:01,820
So we took the all-encompassing Morgan

542
00:23:01,820 --> 00:23:03,940
and broke it into pieces.

543
00:23:03,940 --> 00:23:05,981
And then we looked for themes and play styles

544
00:23:05,981 --> 00:23:07,061
in those pieces.

545
00:23:07,061 --> 00:23:09,002
And there were some that kind of naturally

546
00:23:09,002 --> 00:23:10,562
clumped together in this process.

547
00:23:10,562 --> 00:23:11,983
And there were many different configurations

548
00:23:11,983 --> 00:23:16,724
that we ended up settling on the five that you see there.

549
00:23:16,724 --> 00:23:19,125
So yeah, we looked for themes and play styles

550
00:23:19,125 --> 00:23:20,985
in those clumps.

551
00:23:20,985 --> 00:23:22,946
So you might have more of a tank character,

552
00:23:22,946 --> 00:23:25,667
someone's more of a space wizard kind of guy,

553
00:23:25,667 --> 00:23:27,107
someone's more tech-inclined.

554
00:23:28,348 --> 00:23:30,170
And so from those templates, character traits emerged

555
00:23:30,170 --> 00:23:32,732
and we wrote personalities to go with those.

556
00:23:32,732 --> 00:23:35,454
So the tank becomes VJ, the engineer becomes Joan, et cetera.

557
00:23:35,454 --> 00:23:40,878
And this approach yielded some really cool results

558
00:23:40,878 --> 00:23:42,239
that ended up solving some problems

559
00:23:42,239 --> 00:23:43,980
that we deal with in immersive sims

560
00:23:43,980 --> 00:23:47,403
without that being the intention going into it, right?

561
00:23:47,403 --> 00:23:51,426
So first we lost the sort of choice paralysis you can get

562
00:23:51,426 --> 00:23:53,607
when you get a massive skill tree presented to the player

563
00:23:53,607 --> 00:23:54,428
like right off the bat.

564
00:23:54,967 --> 00:23:56,727
Each character was focused so the player

565
00:23:56,727 --> 00:23:57,647
could make informed decisions.

566
00:23:57,647 --> 00:24:00,408
You know, this character's about dealing damage,

567
00:24:00,408 --> 00:24:01,808
so here are my options to do that, right?

568
00:24:01,808 --> 00:24:04,829
And all the smaller trees, they had enough wiggle room

569
00:24:04,829 --> 00:24:08,349
within them for the player to choose their style,

570
00:24:08,349 --> 00:24:09,590
but they were all heavily themed

571
00:24:09,590 --> 00:24:11,930
so the player was making informed decisions.

572
00:24:11,930 --> 00:24:14,691
And this is an example of the Morgan

573
00:24:14,691 --> 00:24:16,431
overwhelming suite of powers, by the way.

574
00:24:16,431 --> 00:24:20,292
So there was very little overlap in these skills as well

575
00:24:20,292 --> 00:24:21,412
so they could compliment one another.

576
00:24:21,412 --> 00:24:23,493
So maybe one, you know, only Claire, for instance,

577
00:24:23,493 --> 00:24:23,993
had hacking.

578
00:24:24,515 --> 00:24:27,175
So she could go open doors and then other characters

579
00:24:27,175 --> 00:24:32,296
could come in subsequent runs and go through those doors.

580
00:24:32,296 --> 00:24:34,837
Vijay was combat centered so he could go clear an area

581
00:24:34,837 --> 00:24:36,857
of enemies and you come back as another character

582
00:24:36,857 --> 00:24:37,678
and have a bit of a reprieve.

583
00:24:37,678 --> 00:24:41,658
So second, since all these characters are mandatory

584
00:24:41,658 --> 00:24:42,999
at some point or another in the campaign,

585
00:24:42,999 --> 00:24:44,899
we have the potential for pushing the player

586
00:24:44,899 --> 00:24:46,800
outside of their comfort zones.

587
00:24:46,800 --> 00:24:50,000
You know, through the sort of focus skill sets of each one.

588
00:24:50,333 --> 00:24:54,417
One thing about RPGs and immersive sims is players tend to gravitate towards a style.

589
00:24:54,417 --> 00:25:00,863
Game after game after game, like I'm the sneaky person, I'm the gun haver, I'm the whatever,

590
00:25:00,863 --> 00:25:02,625
right?

591
00:25:03,800 --> 00:25:05,701
But by pushing other templates in front of the player,

592
00:25:05,701 --> 00:25:07,702
we can make them see the game from different angles.

593
00:25:07,702 --> 00:25:09,063
And I think that's very valuable.

594
00:25:09,063 --> 00:25:10,584
It can be a double-edged sword,

595
00:25:10,584 --> 00:25:11,985
because some players don't want to

596
00:25:11,985 --> 00:25:13,546
step outside their comfort zone.

597
00:25:13,546 --> 00:25:14,307
It's comfortable.

598
00:25:14,307 --> 00:25:19,050
But I think everything was under a small enough umbrella

599
00:25:19,050 --> 00:25:22,353
in our game that it worked out okay.

600
00:25:22,353 --> 00:25:25,034
Yeah, we weren't making anyone do match three games

601
00:25:25,034 --> 00:25:27,676
or cart race or something as part of their character's

602
00:25:27,676 --> 00:25:28,017
skill sets.

603
00:25:30,672 --> 00:25:33,474
Third, so by playing characters with a set of affinities,

604
00:25:33,474 --> 00:25:34,874
you get out of what I call guilt-driven gameplay.

605
00:25:34,874 --> 00:25:37,415
This is the thing I really liked about Heat Signature

606
00:25:37,415 --> 00:25:37,776
from Tom Francis.

607
00:25:37,776 --> 00:25:40,117
You get these characters that are already

608
00:25:40,117 --> 00:25:42,738
leaning in a direction, so they have a temperament

609
00:25:42,738 --> 00:25:44,719
and the associated tools.

610
00:25:45,495 --> 00:25:47,176
to go in a certain direction, right?

611
00:25:47,176 --> 00:25:48,137
So with Dishonored or Deus Ex,

612
00:25:48,137 --> 00:25:49,678
you can end up playing the whole game

613
00:25:49,678 --> 00:25:51,780
in a very narrow fashion because,

614
00:25:51,780 --> 00:25:53,701
like in my head, Corvo doesn't kill people.

615
00:25:53,701 --> 00:25:56,944
In my head, JC Ditton is never seen by anybody, right?

616
00:25:56,944 --> 00:25:59,406
So you kind of self-impose these limitations

617
00:25:59,406 --> 00:26:00,847
and that can be, that's fine, right?

618
00:26:00,847 --> 00:26:01,828
But you can end up playing.

619
00:26:02,330 --> 00:26:04,711
in a sort of self-flagellating way,

620
00:26:04,711 --> 00:26:06,172
where you're like, okay, I was seen by somebody,

621
00:26:06,172 --> 00:26:07,833
I'm gonna reload my save.

622
00:26:07,833 --> 00:26:08,973
I accidentally killed somebody

623
00:26:08,973 --> 00:26:11,634
because they slid down a hill into the river.

624
00:26:11,634 --> 00:26:13,395
I'm gonna reload my save, right?

625
00:26:13,395 --> 00:26:16,716
Even if the game isn't technically saying you failed,

626
00:26:16,716 --> 00:26:19,017
you're, again, you're imposing that on yourself,

627
00:26:19,017 --> 00:26:21,478
and you end up hating the game in the process sometimes.

628
00:26:22,040 --> 00:26:24,120
So when you're given a variety of characters,

629
00:26:24,120 --> 00:26:25,240
you can break out of that prison for a bit,

630
00:26:25,240 --> 00:26:27,841
because okay, this person is already kind of chaotic,

631
00:26:27,841 --> 00:26:29,701
this person is already very violent,

632
00:26:29,701 --> 00:26:31,521
and I can do that through them

633
00:26:31,521 --> 00:26:33,862
without sullying Corvo's good name

634
00:26:33,862 --> 00:26:35,302
or something like that, right?

635
00:26:35,302 --> 00:26:38,403
Some of the best experiences in Dishonored

636
00:26:38,403 --> 00:26:40,743
came when players would fail their sneaky approach

637
00:26:40,743 --> 00:26:43,244
and then have to sort of improvise in the messy aftermath,

638
00:26:43,244 --> 00:26:46,344
playing like a rat-infested jazz in the process.

639
00:26:46,344 --> 00:26:48,805
Those experiences were completely negated,

640
00:26:48,805 --> 00:26:50,905
again, when the player would just stop and reload.

641
00:26:52,077 --> 00:26:55,440
This also combats ambient anxiety built up

642
00:26:55,440 --> 00:26:56,341
from fear of missing out.

643
00:26:56,341 --> 00:26:58,923
If you're wondering, oh, well, that whole other

644
00:26:58,923 --> 00:27:01,145
skill tree over there, I'll never get to do,

645
00:27:01,145 --> 00:27:01,926
I wonder what it's like.

646
00:27:01,926 --> 00:27:04,408
Or some players are like, okay, I'll play that,

647
00:27:04,408 --> 00:27:06,971
and I'll do my second playthrough with that tree

648
00:27:06,971 --> 00:27:08,652
or something like that, and then they never get to it

649
00:27:08,652 --> 00:27:10,874
because they've got a Steam backlog of 500 games

650
00:27:10,874 --> 00:27:11,255
or something.

651
00:27:15,095 --> 00:27:16,495
So one of the first things we had to decide

652
00:27:16,495 --> 00:27:18,956
after choosing to go roguelike with Mooncrush

653
00:27:18,956 --> 00:27:21,057
was a model of persistence to use

654
00:27:21,057 --> 00:27:22,118
in the characters specifically.

655
00:27:22,118 --> 00:27:24,318
Traditionally, in our games,

656
00:27:24,318 --> 00:27:26,459
death means you have to go back to the last checkpoint

657
00:27:26,459 --> 00:27:27,560
and try again.

658
00:27:27,560 --> 00:27:30,281
Death is outside of the core loop.

659
00:27:30,281 --> 00:27:32,482
It's outside, basically.

660
00:27:32,482 --> 00:27:34,263
In roguelikes, however, death is an expected

661
00:27:34,263 --> 00:27:35,583
and integrated part of the experience

662
00:27:35,583 --> 00:27:38,144
instead of an interruption to that experience.

663
00:27:38,144 --> 00:27:39,865
Now there are loops, basically.

664
00:27:39,865 --> 00:27:41,045
So to adapt to this new model.

665
00:27:41,470 --> 00:27:42,811
We had to decide if we wanted the player

666
00:27:42,811 --> 00:27:45,252
to retain some semblance of progress between runs

667
00:27:45,252 --> 00:27:47,213
or if we wanted to completely wipe the slate clean.

668
00:27:47,213 --> 00:27:50,675
And then what kind of metastructure we wanted to use

669
00:27:50,675 --> 00:27:52,396
to hold the whole thing together in the process.

670
00:27:52,396 --> 00:27:54,837
So we looked at Spelunky and Rogue Legacy

671
00:27:54,837 --> 00:27:57,118
as our sort of go-to examples of two different models,

672
00:27:57,118 --> 00:28:01,881
two different schools of thought.

673
00:28:01,881 --> 00:28:06,043
So Spelunky is this kind of pure expression of replay.

674
00:28:06,043 --> 00:28:07,784
You start on the same footing every single time

675
00:28:07,784 --> 00:28:10,745
with the exception of shortcuts, which don't really count.

676
00:28:11,845 --> 00:28:14,026
you get this sort of stateless, timeless feeling to the game.

677
00:28:14,026 --> 00:28:16,007
It's like checkers or chess or something like that, right?

678
00:28:16,007 --> 00:28:17,668
Other thing that changes over time

679
00:28:17,668 --> 00:28:19,269
is the player's skill level

680
00:28:19,269 --> 00:28:21,790
and the game itself is this immutable thing.

681
00:28:21,790 --> 00:28:24,792
And also due to the random generation of the levels,

682
00:28:24,792 --> 00:28:27,033
you're learning how the systems interlock

683
00:28:27,033 --> 00:28:29,074
instead of memorizing a layout,

684
00:28:29,074 --> 00:28:30,495
you're learning a language

685
00:28:30,495 --> 00:28:32,055
rather than memorizing a piece of music.

686
00:28:32,055 --> 00:28:33,656
Rogue Legacy, on the other hand,

687
00:28:33,656 --> 00:28:35,117
has a progression system that persists

688
00:28:35,117 --> 00:28:35,957
between your trips to the castle.

689
00:28:35,957 --> 00:28:37,998
So you're not mechanically expected

690
00:28:37,998 --> 00:28:39,539
to be able to beat the game until many runs in.

691
00:28:39,539 --> 00:28:41,580
Some people do it, but they're outliers.

692
00:28:42,052 --> 00:28:45,694
But every death, you get to bring experience points

693
00:28:45,694 --> 00:28:47,875
and gold and things back to give you

694
00:28:47,875 --> 00:28:49,776
this sort of incremental advancement

695
00:28:49,776 --> 00:28:51,397
to push you over slumps in progress.

696
00:28:51,397 --> 00:28:55,659
It's a really effective negative feedback system

697
00:28:55,659 --> 00:28:57,440
that also keeps you playing in light of defeat.

698
00:28:57,440 --> 00:29:00,322
And so ultimately, we settled on the latter model,

699
00:29:00,322 --> 00:29:03,244
the Rogue Legacy model, mainly because,

700
00:29:03,244 --> 00:29:05,625
for one, the character progression in Rogue Legacy

701
00:29:05,625 --> 00:29:07,306
mapped really well to what we were already doing

702
00:29:07,306 --> 00:29:09,487
with character skill trees in Prey.

703
00:29:09,938 --> 00:29:11,159
And character skill trees are something

704
00:29:11,159 --> 00:29:13,219
that generally play best over multiple sessions.

705
00:29:13,219 --> 00:29:15,260
We had this one model that we entertained

706
00:29:15,260 --> 00:29:17,020
where you would have the skill tree

707
00:29:17,020 --> 00:29:19,401
but it would reset every single time.

708
00:29:19,401 --> 00:29:21,702
But that ended up being way too tedious in our heads

709
00:29:21,702 --> 00:29:23,662
of having to spin those points every single time

710
00:29:23,662 --> 00:29:25,182
you get killed or something.

711
00:29:25,182 --> 00:29:28,143
And we also eventually decided we wanted

712
00:29:28,143 --> 00:29:30,044
to have an overarching story to narratively tie

713
00:29:30,044 --> 00:29:31,004
this game to the franchise.

714
00:29:31,004 --> 00:29:33,385
And that worked best with a sense of progression

715
00:29:33,385 --> 00:29:34,625
doled out over multiple sessions

716
00:29:34,625 --> 00:29:38,526
rather than one sort of stateless experience like Spelunky.

717
00:29:41,596 --> 00:29:42,477
Oh, there we go.

718
00:29:42,477 --> 00:29:44,978
So the next question is what do we want to persist

719
00:29:44,978 --> 00:29:45,639
in the world?

720
00:29:45,639 --> 00:29:48,981
So you've got character progression and world progression

721
00:29:48,981 --> 00:29:50,703
and state, basically, you have to kind of keep track of.

722
00:29:50,703 --> 00:29:54,025
So we wanted to keep a sense of agency in the game.

723
00:29:54,025 --> 00:29:56,027
You know, the player having some kind of lasting impact

724
00:29:56,027 --> 00:29:58,529
on the world, but we also kind of wanted to have our cake

725
00:29:58,529 --> 00:29:59,049
and eat it too.

726
00:29:59,049 --> 00:30:01,631
We wanted, you know, the sort of fresh start of a roguelike

727
00:30:01,631 --> 00:30:04,593
where you can try new things without the baggage

728
00:30:04,593 --> 00:30:06,735
of previous mistakes.

729
00:30:07,577 --> 00:30:09,219
And we knew we'd have to reset the world at some points

730
00:30:09,219 --> 00:30:11,422
to make the escapes challenging and repopulate monsters

731
00:30:11,422 --> 00:30:12,103
and things like that.

732
00:30:12,103 --> 00:30:15,828
So we introduced the concept of resetting the simulation,

733
00:30:15,828 --> 00:30:17,370
again, to sort of have both.

734
00:30:17,370 --> 00:30:21,716
The conceit is that everything in the world persists

735
00:30:21,716 --> 00:30:24,399
until all five of your, or however many characters you have,

736
00:30:24,399 --> 00:30:25,921
until they're all dead or have escaped.

737
00:30:26,557 --> 00:30:28,138
and then things are reset.

738
00:30:28,138 --> 00:30:30,740
So each character gets one life, basically.

739
00:30:30,740 --> 00:30:34,022
So for instance, Joan might make her way

740
00:30:34,022 --> 00:30:35,603
into the shuttle and escapes,

741
00:30:35,603 --> 00:30:36,764
and now she's no longer playable

742
00:30:36,764 --> 00:30:38,645
for the rest of that run of the simulation.

743
00:30:38,645 --> 00:30:41,587
Then the player picks up Vijay and goes and dies

744
00:30:41,587 --> 00:30:44,449
in the middle of the crater to the moon shark,

745
00:30:44,449 --> 00:30:45,590
and he's no longer available,

746
00:30:45,590 --> 00:30:47,811
and now there's like a phantom with his name on it

747
00:30:47,811 --> 00:30:48,612
carrying all of his stuff.

748
00:30:48,612 --> 00:30:50,253
I'll talk more about that later.

749
00:30:51,307 --> 00:30:53,648
So then the player comes back in as Claire,

750
00:30:53,648 --> 00:30:56,230
and she can either go fight the VJ phantom,

751
00:30:56,230 --> 00:30:58,772
or she can go try to make an escape, or whatever,

752
00:30:58,772 --> 00:31:00,594
and so on until everyone's dead or has escaped.

753
00:31:00,594 --> 00:31:04,477
So doing this meant we got the roguelike consequences

754
00:31:04,477 --> 00:31:06,778
of permadeath, sort of, as well as the ability

755
00:31:06,778 --> 00:31:08,379
to have interplay between the characters

756
00:31:08,379 --> 00:31:11,222
and a meaningful player impact on the world.

757
00:31:11,222 --> 00:31:13,423
That, and we'll talk about this in a second, actually.

758
00:31:13,423 --> 00:31:15,024
Maybe the next slide.

759
00:31:15,024 --> 00:31:18,367
Yeah, so this adaptation ended up as a happy compromise

760
00:31:18,367 --> 00:31:20,248
between the new and the old.

761
00:31:21,729 --> 00:31:25,351
So yeah, speaking to that, you get this concept

762
00:31:25,351 --> 00:31:26,712
of an afterlife when you do this,

763
00:31:26,712 --> 00:31:28,953
the sort of persistence in the world.

764
00:31:28,953 --> 00:31:31,074
It's a legacy you're leaving for yourself.

765
00:31:31,074 --> 00:31:33,015
We really like the idea of the player

766
00:31:33,015 --> 00:31:35,496
sort of playing a co-op game with themselves in a way.

767
00:31:35,496 --> 00:31:38,097
And this adds a layer to the emergent nature

768
00:31:38,097 --> 00:31:39,858
of these kinds of games as well.

769
00:31:39,858 --> 00:31:41,999
So if you get interesting combinations

770
00:31:41,999 --> 00:31:44,221
based on the abilities and equipment of one player,

771
00:31:44,221 --> 00:31:45,741
you can only imagine what you can string together

772
00:31:45,741 --> 00:31:48,643
if that player can leave stuff for another player,

773
00:31:48,643 --> 00:31:49,763
another character.

