00:32:08,889 --> 00:32:11,071
those enemies will still be there for the next character,

781
00:32:11,071 --> 00:32:14,934
so you have to think a few moves ahead, basically.

782
00:32:14,934 --> 00:32:16,655
And lastly, as I mentioned earlier,

783
00:32:16,655 --> 00:32:18,336
we added this wrinkle where characters that die

784
00:32:18,336 --> 00:32:21,438
come back as phantoms for other characters to deal with.

785
00:32:21,996 --> 00:32:23,617
So if you die with a lot of cool stuff,

786
00:32:23,617 --> 00:32:25,979
you'll have to fight a monster with that cool stuff

787
00:32:25,979 --> 00:32:27,360
to get it back.

788
00:32:27,360 --> 00:32:29,302
It's much more interesting, or it was more interesting

789
00:32:29,302 --> 00:32:31,324
to us than just picking your crap up

790
00:32:31,324 --> 00:32:33,265
off the ground, basically.

791
00:32:33,265 --> 00:32:35,807
It adds this sort of dynamic piece to the board

792
00:32:35,807 --> 00:32:38,870
that you now have to deal with because of your ineptitude

793
00:32:38,870 --> 00:32:39,490
in a previous run.

794
00:32:39,490 --> 00:32:46,216
All right, so let's look at replay and game length.

795
00:32:46,216 --> 00:32:51,620
So this is a diagram.

796
00:32:52,055 --> 00:32:55,596
of a narrative-driven linear AAA game.

797
00:32:55,596 --> 00:32:56,717
I guess it doesn't have to be AAA,

798
00:32:56,717 --> 00:32:58,998
but a narrative-driven linear game.

799
00:32:58,998 --> 00:33:01,239
The dollar bills here represent budget allocation

