00:34:32,295 --> 00:34:33,835
Some don't even finish it.

837
00:34:33,835 --> 00:34:36,897
But if they only play through one time,

838
00:34:36,897 --> 00:34:38,418
then maybe they don't know there were choices.

839
00:34:38,418 --> 00:34:40,479
They don't see the breadth of the whole thing

840
00:34:40,479 --> 00:34:42,900
through their single play through.

841
00:34:44,195 --> 00:34:46,416
So we looked at this phenomenon going into Mooncrash

842
00:34:46,416 --> 00:34:49,437
and the effect it has on the player's sense of agency

843
00:34:49,437 --> 00:34:50,857
and choice and outcomes.

844
00:34:50,857 --> 00:34:53,357
So if you've got a game that's 15 hours long

845
00:34:53,357 --> 00:34:55,558
and there are choices to be made in the beginning

846
00:34:55,558 --> 00:34:57,558
or the middle or wherever, actually,

847
00:34:57,558 --> 00:34:59,399
by the time the player finishes the game

848
00:34:59,399 --> 00:35:00,939
and comes back to those choices,

849
00:35:00,939 --> 00:35:02,279
it's possible they won't even remember

850
00:35:02,279 --> 00:35:04,100
what they did the first time around

851
00:35:04,100 --> 00:35:05,100
or what the outcome was.

852
00:35:05,100 --> 00:35:07,021
And this is assuming they even knew

853
00:35:07,021 --> 00:35:08,401
there was a choice happening at all,

854
00:35:08,401 --> 00:35:12,722
assumes that the player finished in the first place

855
00:35:12,722 --> 00:35:14,102
and didn't just move on to another game.

856
00:35:15,610 --> 00:35:16,471
If you've got a shorter game,

857
00:35:16,471 --> 00:35:18,173
players are more likely to remember those choices

858
00:35:18,173 --> 00:35:19,774
in the short time it takes for them

859
00:35:19,774 --> 00:35:21,015
to get back to the choice.

860
00:35:21,015 --> 00:35:25,079
And they're also more likely to play the game multiple times

861
00:35:25,079 --> 00:35:26,220
to experiment with different outcomes.

862
00:35:26,220 --> 00:35:28,923
Additionally, there's a phenomenon we discovered

863
00:35:28,923 --> 00:35:30,344
with player choice in games

864
00:35:30,344 --> 00:35:34,268
when we were playtesting Dishonored with people

865
00:35:34,268 --> 00:35:36,870
is that if the choice is too subtle and organic,

866
00:35:36,870 --> 00:35:39,172
players don't know they even made one.

867
00:35:39,438 --> 00:35:40,779
And this can be really great for immersion,

868
00:35:40,779 --> 00:35:43,540
again, I'm not saying you shouldn't do this,

869
00:35:43,540 --> 00:35:46,102
but it's a phenomenon that we noticed.

870
00:35:46,102 --> 00:35:48,303
We did a play test with the first hour of the game

871
00:35:48,303 --> 00:35:50,925
with some people, and everyone at the end were like,

872
00:35:50,925 --> 00:35:53,426
yeah, we played this, and it's a pretty linear experience,

873
00:35:53,426 --> 00:35:54,807
I went and killed this person,

874
00:35:54,807 --> 00:35:56,468
or infiltrated this place, or whatever,

875
00:35:56,468 --> 00:35:58,449
and then the person next to them would turn around

876
00:35:58,449 --> 00:35:59,170
and be like, you met who?

877
00:35:59,170 --> 00:35:59,610
You went where?

878
00:35:59,610 --> 00:36:01,371
And then when they compared notes,

879
00:36:01,371 --> 00:36:04,553
they could see the breadth of the space,

880
00:36:04,553 --> 00:36:06,334
but only then, because everything was so organic.

881
00:36:07,595 --> 00:36:10,556
it was all based on their sort of moving through the space

882
00:36:10,556 --> 00:36:12,537
instead of a hard choice, like a big left or right,

883
00:36:12,537 --> 00:36:13,657
or A or B, or something like that.

884
00:36:13,657 --> 00:36:18,179
So to address all these kind of ideas in Mooncrash,

885
00:36:18,179 --> 00:36:21,860
we adapted the more roguelike approach,

886
00:36:21,860 --> 00:36:25,682
and so we wanted to shorten the replay loops for starters.

887
00:36:25,682 --> 00:36:27,243
A single pass through the campaign

888
00:36:27,243 --> 00:36:31,104
would actually involve several passes through the content,

889
00:36:31,104 --> 00:36:32,325
several loops through the content.

890
00:36:32,903 --> 00:36:38,128
And by a pass through the content I mean like traveling through a few different levels to do an escape

891
00:36:38,128 --> 00:36:43,692
Or completing a story mission or maybe just dying as the result of a plan gone wrong

892
00:36:43,692 --> 00:36:50,238
And this results in the player seeing a large percentage of the game and developing a familiarity with the world

893
00:36:51,611 --> 00:36:54,093
One problem this model can cause, however,

894
00:36:54,093 --> 00:36:56,275
and you can probably guess from the diagram here,

895
00:36:56,275 --> 00:36:57,837
is boredom from repetition.

896
00:36:57,837 --> 00:36:59,298
You see everything is kind of branching off

897
00:36:59,298 --> 00:37:01,900
of that one root, so that one section of the game

898
00:37:01,900 --> 00:37:03,822
is gonna get very stale very fast,

899
00:37:03,822 --> 00:37:05,584
it's the alarm clock from Groundhog Day,

900
00:37:05,584 --> 00:37:07,025
basically, over and over again.

901
00:37:07,025 --> 00:37:11,689
So to address that, oh, this is the same diagram,

902
00:37:11,689 --> 00:37:14,832
more accurate, with loops and dotted lines and stuff,

903
00:37:14,832 --> 00:37:18,035
but this is a lot to swallow, so, yeah.

904
00:37:19,898 --> 00:37:22,700
So to counter this, we had multiple starting locations

905
00:37:22,700 --> 00:37:23,680
in the game.

906
00:37:23,680 --> 00:37:24,681
So when a new character started,

907
00:37:24,681 --> 00:37:26,442
they would start in a different location

908
00:37:26,442 --> 00:37:28,023
than the previous character.

909
00:37:28,023 --> 00:37:29,504
But they would be in the same level

910
00:37:29,504 --> 00:37:31,406
that they had died in as that previous character,

911
00:37:31,406 --> 00:37:32,847
or escaped in.

912
00:37:32,847 --> 00:37:34,748
Part of this was purely logistics.

913
00:37:34,748 --> 00:37:37,270
We wanted to negate load times as much as possible,

914
00:37:37,270 --> 00:37:38,751
especially when you're doing loopy stuff.

915
00:37:38,751 --> 00:37:41,433
Load times can really kill the game.

916
00:37:41,433 --> 00:37:42,593
But also it had the side effect

917
00:37:42,593 --> 00:37:43,934
of keeping the player moving forward

918
00:37:43,934 --> 00:37:46,176
because they could basically start really close

919
00:37:46,176 --> 00:37:48,377
to the kind of scattered remains of their last run

920
00:37:48,377 --> 00:37:48,978
if they had failed.

921
00:37:49,463 --> 00:37:52,964
so they'd pick up and know exactly where they needed to go.

922
00:37:52,964 --> 00:37:55,145
It's worth noting that this concept

923
00:37:55,145 --> 00:37:56,806
can be taken too far as well.

924
00:37:56,806 --> 00:37:57,786
Some of our earlier models,

925
00:37:57,786 --> 00:38:00,627
we had the player start in any level, in any location,

926
00:38:00,627 --> 00:38:03,028
all these random spots basically,

927
00:38:03,028 --> 00:38:05,329
but it got really disorienting really fast,

928
00:38:05,329 --> 00:38:06,149
and the players wouldn't,

929
00:38:06,149 --> 00:38:09,371
it would take them a while to get back into the context

930
00:38:09,371 --> 00:38:11,051
of what they needed to be doing and where to go and stuff.

931
00:38:11,051 --> 00:38:13,952
So even with these varying spawns though,

932
00:38:13,952 --> 00:38:16,913
you're gonna have the potential for boredom

933
00:38:16,913 --> 00:38:18,394
due to overexposure to the same content.

934
00:38:22,449 --> 00:38:26,252
Let's talk about that.

935
00:38:26,252 --> 00:38:28,474
So earlier I mentioned how systemic design

936
00:38:28,474 --> 00:38:29,814
and focusing on process intensity

937
00:38:29,814 --> 00:38:32,296
helps lengthen the experience for the player.

938
00:38:32,296 --> 00:38:35,198
You get more output for your input as a developer.

939
00:38:35,630 --> 00:38:40,953
The dark side of this can be a game that keeps the player playing even when the novel experiences have run dry.

940
00:38:40,953 --> 00:38:46,216
We dipped our toes into random content shuffling in generations, so this topic became very relevant to us.

941
00:38:46,216 --> 00:38:49,998
The concept of infinite content, it can be a facade over an endless grind, basically.

942
00:38:49,998 --> 00:38:53,300
You know, by the time your game stops having something new to show the player,

943
00:38:53,300 --> 00:38:56,161
it should make a graceful exit instead of trying to compel them to stick around.

944
00:38:56,787 --> 00:39:00,168
This isn't always an obvious choice as a developer either.

945
00:39:00,168 --> 00:39:01,528
There can be a lot of times where you're like,

946
00:39:01,528 --> 00:39:03,369
oh yeah, I can easily generate another three hours

947
00:39:03,369 --> 00:39:04,889
of game here for the player

948
00:39:04,889 --> 00:39:06,710
just by doing this one little thing, right?

949
00:39:06,710 --> 00:39:08,791
The players want more game, right?

950
00:39:08,791 --> 00:39:09,931
Have some more pancakes, player.

951
00:39:09,931 --> 00:39:12,992
So there's not always malevolence behind this.

952
00:39:12,992 --> 00:39:15,833
So instead of focusing on the amount of variability

953
00:39:15,833 --> 00:39:18,114
we were offering, we started filtering

954
00:39:18,114 --> 00:39:20,374
for meaningful variability.

955
00:39:20,374 --> 00:39:23,335
So what could we offer that was different

956
00:39:23,335 --> 00:39:26,597
from session to session in a tangibly meaningful way?

957
00:39:27,338 --> 00:39:29,621
So in this straw man example above,

958
00:39:29,621 --> 00:39:32,185
I could say TV static offers the viewer

959
00:39:32,185 --> 00:39:35,190
hundreds of unique images every minute.

960
00:39:35,190 --> 00:39:37,313
It's ridiculously exaggerated, but.

961
00:39:37,925 --> 00:39:41,346
It sort of speaks to this one exaggerated extension,

962
00:39:41,346 --> 00:39:42,326
or this one approach.

963
00:39:42,326 --> 00:39:44,687
It's very scalable, basically.

964
00:39:44,687 --> 00:39:46,988
But the thing about TV static is not only

965
00:39:46,988 --> 00:39:50,089
are the images individually meaningless to the viewer,

966
00:39:50,089 --> 00:39:52,010
they're also individual, or sorry,

967
00:39:52,010 --> 00:39:54,450
they're meaninglessly different from one another,

968
00:39:54,450 --> 00:39:56,531
from frame to frame, basically.

969
00:39:56,531 --> 00:39:59,412
A more gamey example might be a dungeon that's randomized,

970
00:39:59,412 --> 00:40:01,053
but you're only changing the color of the tiles

971
00:40:01,053 --> 00:40:03,274
on the floor or something like that.

972
00:40:03,274 --> 00:40:04,734
The opposite of the spectrum.

973
00:40:05,212 --> 00:40:06,692
is to handcraft everything individually

974
00:40:06,692 --> 00:40:07,873
and that doesn't scale very well at all.

975
00:40:07,873 --> 00:40:11,574
So in Mooncrash, one of the ways we tackled this

976
00:40:11,574 --> 00:40:13,975
was through what we called hazard channels.

977
00:40:13,975 --> 00:40:16,236
So we took each of the four environments,

978
00:40:16,236 --> 00:40:18,537
the four levels, and we layered on top of them

979
00:40:18,537 --> 00:40:19,777
five different hazard states.

980
00:40:19,777 --> 00:40:21,958
So you've got fire, radiation, flooding,

981
00:40:21,958 --> 00:40:24,479
the power can be out, you can be oxygen deprived, right?

982
00:40:24,479 --> 00:40:27,140
Some of these had to be offered.

983
00:40:27,140 --> 00:40:28,981
You can see like the fire, for instance,

984
00:40:28,981 --> 00:40:31,762
requires VFX and mesh alterations and things like that.

985
00:40:31,762 --> 00:40:34,583
Radiation and flooding also need custom geo,

986
00:40:34,583 --> 00:40:34,923
but.

987
00:40:36,528 --> 00:40:38,030
We authored these all in chunks,

988
00:40:38,030 --> 00:40:39,671
so then they could be mixed and matched.

989
00:40:39,671 --> 00:40:41,232
So any one particular level that was on fire

990
00:40:41,232 --> 00:40:44,294
could have five different versions of being on fire

991
00:40:44,294 --> 00:40:47,036
with different rooms being affected and things like that.

992
00:40:47,036 --> 00:40:51,460
Yeah, so these states could then be layered

993
00:40:51,460 --> 00:40:53,421
on top of each other in different combinations as well.

994
00:40:53,421 --> 00:40:55,363
So you could have fire and radiation,

995
00:40:55,363 --> 00:40:58,745
you could have the power be out and it could be on fire,

996
00:40:58,745 --> 00:40:59,606
things like that.

997
00:40:59,606 --> 00:41:02,008
Some of these were mutually exclusive,

998
00:41:02,008 --> 00:41:03,409
so if there was no oxygen in a level,

999
00:41:03,409 --> 00:41:04,670
then it couldn't be on fire.

1000
00:41:04,670 --> 00:41:06,111
And then some modified each other,

1001
00:41:06,111 --> 00:41:06,291
so.

1002
00:41:06,832 --> 00:41:07,832
Normally if there's flooding,

1003
00:41:07,832 --> 00:41:08,913
then you have electrical hazards,

1004
00:41:08,913 --> 00:41:09,773
but if the power was out,

1005
00:41:09,773 --> 00:41:11,474
then you had flooding without the electrical hazards

1006
00:41:11,474 --> 00:41:12,014
and things like that.

1007
00:41:12,014 --> 00:41:14,036
So you had these interesting sort of combinations.

1008
00:41:14,036 --> 00:41:16,397
What this gave us was really strong.

1009
00:41:16,397 --> 00:41:18,778
So the combination of channels gave us a lot of outputs

1010
00:41:18,778 --> 00:41:19,479
over a few inputs.

1011
00:41:19,479 --> 00:41:22,340
And that was especially given the fact

1012
00:41:22,340 --> 00:41:23,481
that it was a DLC team, small, you know,

1013
00:41:23,481 --> 00:41:25,862
small scrappy team.

1014
00:41:25,862 --> 00:41:28,223
The spaces could be recontextualized

1015
00:41:28,223 --> 00:41:30,004
meaningfully for the player.

1016
00:41:30,004 --> 00:41:32,366
So, you know, the staircase that you see here

1017
00:41:32,366 --> 00:41:32,786
is normally

1018
00:41:33,525 --> 00:41:37,426
perfectly fine, you can walk up it and there's no problem,

1019
00:41:37,426 --> 00:41:38,987
but when it's on fire, now you have to decide

1020
00:41:38,987 --> 00:41:40,387
if you want to find another way around

1021
00:41:40,387 --> 00:41:43,649
or use your player tools or things like that.

1022
00:41:43,649 --> 00:41:45,409
The spaces also look dramatically different

1023
00:41:45,409 --> 00:41:49,351
in subsequent visits while remaining recognizable.

1024
00:41:49,351 --> 00:41:52,632
So this means you get visual interest over time,

1025
00:41:52,632 --> 00:41:54,753
but since we're not randomizing the layout of the level,

1026
00:41:54,753 --> 00:41:56,754
you can actually learn these spaces.

1027
00:41:56,754 --> 00:41:59,215
So the staircase will always be the staircase,

1028
00:41:59,215 --> 00:42:02,356
but now it's different tactically and visually.

1029
00:42:04,332 --> 00:42:09,356
Also, power outages cause, there's a tram that connects levels, and so power outages

1030
00:42:09,356 --> 00:42:10,858
can cause it to malfunction.

1031
00:42:10,858 --> 00:42:15,141
So it overhauls the topography of the game every time, basically, so you have to decide

1032
00:42:15,141 --> 00:42:17,823
which levels, or you have to learn which levels are connected to each other.

1033
00:42:17,823 --> 00:42:23,328
So your approach from level A to B might be completely different in subsequent visits.

1034
00:42:23,328 --> 00:42:32,075
And so this is the same staircase, without the fire, for instance.

1035
00:42:33,165 --> 00:42:34,986
You can see here, whoop, did I skip?

1036
00:42:34,986 --> 00:42:37,168
Yeah, okay, here's some just brief examples

1037
00:42:37,168 --> 00:42:42,231
of flooded and electrical, normal, radiation, et cetera.

1038
00:42:42,231 --> 00:42:52,477
Oh, and this is, yeah, without fire, with fire.

1039
00:42:52,477 --> 00:42:57,980
And so we worked a lot with the granularity

1040
00:42:57,980 --> 00:43:00,041
and frequency of the random elements within the levels.

1041
00:43:00,886 --> 00:43:02,968
We found that if every level had a little bit

1042
00:43:02,968 --> 00:43:05,550
of everything in it, it was what I call

1043
00:43:05,550 --> 00:43:06,711
the chopped salad effect.

1044
00:43:06,711 --> 00:43:08,773
Basically, you've got a lot of ingredients in the salad,

1045
00:43:08,773 --> 00:43:11,735
but every bite tastes the same as the last one.

1046
00:43:11,735 --> 00:43:13,056
The same thing with the levels.

1047
00:43:13,056 --> 00:43:15,558
Your net sort of impression going from level one

1048
00:43:15,558 --> 00:43:17,840
to level two here is gonna be the same.

1049
00:43:17,840 --> 00:43:20,202
These two levels are almost 100% different from one another,

1050
00:43:20,202 --> 00:43:23,484
but like the TV static, they're not meaningfully different

1051
00:43:23,484 --> 00:43:25,326
from one another.

1052
00:43:25,326 --> 00:43:29,169
So what we ended up doing was sort of consolidating

1053
00:43:29,169 --> 00:43:29,770
and clumping.

1054
00:43:29,930 --> 00:43:31,612
these random elements.

1055
00:43:31,612 --> 00:43:33,996
So now you've got one that's primarily fire

1056
00:43:33,996 --> 00:43:35,659
and one that's primarily radiation.

1057
00:43:35,659 --> 00:43:39,926
And so your net impression from going from one to the other

1058
00:43:39,926 --> 00:43:41,087
is very palpable, basically.

1059
00:43:41,087 --> 00:43:44,172
And then, let's see.

1060
00:43:45,053 --> 00:43:48,575
Yeah, this also works temporally as well as spatially.

1061
00:43:48,575 --> 00:43:50,997
So when you revisit these levels subsequent times

1062
00:43:50,997 --> 00:43:54,439
and subsequent resets of the simulation,

1063
00:43:54,439 --> 00:43:56,280
you get again a very different impression

1064
00:43:56,280 --> 00:43:57,421
each time you visit it,

1065
00:43:57,421 --> 00:44:00,282
instead of the sort of samey kind of chopped salad effect.

1066
00:44:00,282 --> 00:44:03,805
And this also was echoed in our enemy encounter design

1067
00:44:03,805 --> 00:44:07,307
and several other random elements that we did

1068
00:44:07,307 --> 00:44:09,809
over the course of the game.

1069
00:44:09,809 --> 00:44:12,850
Here's an actual level layout with the same concept applied.

1070
00:44:12,850 --> 00:44:13,771
Chopped up version and.

1071
00:44:16,312 --> 00:44:17,452
the more consolidated version.

1072
00:44:17,452 --> 00:44:27,138
Another way to add variety to the game

1073
00:44:27,138 --> 00:44:28,239
was the corruption meter.

1074
00:44:28,239 --> 00:44:30,800
So this kept the player from just kind of hanging out

1075
00:44:30,800 --> 00:44:35,022
in the game and pushed them to accomplish their goals.

1076
00:44:35,022 --> 00:44:36,663
We ratcheted up the difficulty

1077
00:44:36,663 --> 00:44:38,965
during the time they spend in the simulation

1078
00:44:38,965 --> 00:44:40,606
and we culminate in a forced reset

1079
00:44:40,606 --> 00:44:43,067
after the sort of corruption meter hits level five.

1080
00:44:43,724 --> 00:44:47,247
This was inspired partly by Risk of Rain's difficulty system,

1081
00:44:47,247 --> 00:44:48,989
as well as the ghost in Spelunky.

1082
00:44:48,989 --> 00:44:50,691
We liked how it makes the player choose

1083
00:44:50,691 --> 00:44:53,674
between kind of taking their time to gather resources

1084
00:44:53,674 --> 00:44:56,977
and sort of pushing them forward to accomplish their goals.

1085
00:44:56,977 --> 00:44:58,979
It also adds a layer of variability to the experience

1086
00:44:58,979 --> 00:45:01,161
because further down the corruption meter

1087
00:45:01,161 --> 00:45:02,522
you get different encounters with enemies

1088
00:45:02,522 --> 00:45:03,183
and things like that.

1089
00:45:03,183 --> 00:45:05,786
This was one of the more contentious adaptations

1090
00:45:05,786 --> 00:45:07,387
we made, honestly.

1091
00:45:07,703 --> 00:45:09,044
A lot of people thought it kind of undercut

1092
00:45:09,044 --> 00:45:10,704
the exploratory nature of our games.

1093
00:45:10,704 --> 00:45:13,525
We mitigated it some with these items

1094
00:45:13,525 --> 00:45:16,406
that you can get that reset the clock or wind it back some.

1095
00:45:16,406 --> 00:45:20,128
But at the end of the day, it was something

1096
00:45:20,128 --> 00:45:21,988
that some people didn't like.

1097
00:45:21,988 --> 00:45:24,229
It was an intentional design decision and yeah.

1098
00:45:24,229 --> 00:45:28,631
One of the larger departures from Prey

1099
00:45:28,631 --> 00:45:31,752
was the concept of narrative progression in Mooncrash.

1100
00:45:31,752 --> 00:45:34,873
So the game primarily consists of a series of orders

1101
00:45:34,873 --> 00:45:36,053
from the main character's employer.

1102
00:45:36,053 --> 00:45:37,093
The larger.

1103
00:45:37,437 --> 00:45:39,158
the percent of items checked off the list,

1104
00:45:39,158 --> 00:45:42,039
the farther along the framing story progresses, basically.

1105
00:45:42,039 --> 00:45:44,299
But the player can take these things in any order.

1106
00:45:44,299 --> 00:45:47,780
There are some that have a sort of dependency chain,

1107
00:45:47,780 --> 00:45:49,941
but otherwise you can take them in whatever order you want.

1108
00:45:49,941 --> 00:45:52,562
The actual items are more than just fetch questy stuff

1109
00:45:52,562 --> 00:45:54,622
as well, some of them are entire story missions

1110
00:45:54,622 --> 00:45:56,983
or elaborate escape methods or things like that.

1111
00:45:56,983 --> 00:45:59,184
The point of it is to allow the player

1112
00:45:59,184 --> 00:46:00,344
to proceed at their own pace.

1113
00:46:00,708 --> 00:46:02,129
and in the order that they choose.

1114
00:46:02,129 --> 00:46:04,230
This opens the door for different strategies as well

1115
00:46:04,230 --> 00:46:05,431
and caters to different play styles.

1116
00:46:05,431 --> 00:46:08,412
So some players might want to save big stuff for last

1117
00:46:08,412 --> 00:46:09,733
or focus on one character at a time

1118
00:46:09,733 --> 00:46:11,514
or go on a collecting spree or things like that.

1119
00:46:11,514 --> 00:46:13,636
This is also a win for us

1120
00:46:13,636 --> 00:46:16,217
because we could decouple the player's actions.

1121
00:46:16,705 --> 00:46:19,047
from the prescribed narrative thrust of the game.

1122
00:46:19,047 --> 00:46:20,789
We didn't have to deal with problems like,

1123
00:46:20,789 --> 00:46:21,870
well, what if the player goes over here

1124
00:46:21,870 --> 00:46:24,472
and gets this thing before they find this other thing?

1125
00:46:24,472 --> 00:46:28,035
Or once they've done X, what is their motivation

1126
00:46:28,035 --> 00:46:28,935
to then proceed to Y?

1127
00:46:28,935 --> 00:46:32,138
That was a big deal on Prey because the entire game

1128
00:46:32,138 --> 00:46:36,581
was this sort of continuous string of cause and effect.

1129
00:46:36,581 --> 00:46:38,743
But this sort of unasked those questions.

1130
00:46:40,964 --> 00:46:42,646
And here you can see a brief example

1131
00:46:42,646 --> 00:46:44,147
of the elements that change over time

1132
00:46:44,147 --> 00:46:46,068
as the player finishes items from the list.

1133
00:46:46,068 --> 00:46:49,632
So you get more hazards introduced to the simulation,

1134
00:46:49,632 --> 00:46:52,354
the corruption meter gets faster over time,

1135
00:46:52,354 --> 00:46:54,055
the player's mastery of the space

1136
00:46:54,055 --> 00:46:55,757
is basically tested more and more

1137
00:46:55,757 --> 00:47:06,486
the further along they get to the end of the campaign.

1138
00:47:06,486 --> 00:47:08,408
Finally, the escapes.

1139
00:47:09,004 --> 00:47:10,765
So yeah, one of the first drafts of Mooncrash

1140
00:47:10,765 --> 00:47:13,528
was basically reusing Talos from the core game

1141
00:47:13,528 --> 00:47:15,549
and just adding, like opening the whole thing up

1142
00:47:15,549 --> 00:47:17,431
and adding random escape methods to it.

1143
00:47:17,431 --> 00:47:19,172
Partly inspired by this game called Monstrum

1144
00:47:19,172 --> 00:47:21,394
where you're on this freight ship escaping an alien,

1145
00:47:21,394 --> 00:47:25,858
or sorry, a monster that's escaped and is with you.

1146
00:47:25,858 --> 00:47:29,060
So the Talos version was a much lighter weight version

1147
00:47:29,060 --> 00:47:31,382
of what we ended up doing within Mooncrash,

1148
00:47:31,382 --> 00:47:34,424
but the overarching concept of this sort of escape,

1149
00:47:34,424 --> 00:47:36,366
the randomized escape remained interesting to us.

1150
00:47:37,155 --> 00:47:40,036
So the base in Mooncrash has five different ways to escape.

1151
00:47:40,036 --> 00:47:41,656
Each one is mechanically and thematically

1152
00:47:41,656 --> 00:47:42,616
different from the other.

1153
00:47:42,616 --> 00:47:45,757
So there are a few examples.

1154
00:47:45,757 --> 00:47:47,718
One is a shuttle that requires a character

1155
00:47:47,718 --> 00:47:48,618
to install a piloting skill,

1156
00:47:48,618 --> 00:47:51,079
but you have to find the random location

1157
00:47:51,079 --> 00:47:52,800
of the last person to install that skill

1158
00:47:52,800 --> 00:47:55,481
using the personnel locating system, basically.

1159
00:47:55,481 --> 00:47:57,341
And then that skill persists

1160
00:47:57,341 --> 00:47:58,562
for whatever character installs it,

1161
00:47:58,562 --> 00:48:00,702
so that person can now use that escape method

1162
00:48:00,702 --> 00:48:02,203
once they've got that skill.

1163
00:48:04,175 --> 00:48:06,556
One of them is a cargo container you can stow away in

1164
00:48:06,556 --> 00:48:10,659
and get blasted by rail gun to Earth, basically.

1165
00:48:10,659 --> 00:48:13,280
But first you've got a scavenge

1166
00:48:13,280 --> 00:48:16,102
for a randomized list of supplies, basically,

1167
00:48:16,102 --> 00:48:18,043
so you can survive the trip to Earth.

1168
00:48:18,043 --> 00:48:21,385
One of them is an experimental portal,

1169
00:48:21,385 --> 00:48:23,406
but you need hacking and repair,

1170
00:48:23,406 --> 00:48:25,547
which are separated into two different characters.

1171
00:48:25,547 --> 00:48:27,208
So those two characters have to work together

1172
00:48:27,208 --> 00:48:29,590
to enable this escape method to even function.

1173
00:48:30,527 --> 00:48:32,128
So these differences kept the game interesting

1174
00:48:32,128 --> 00:48:34,630
by varying up the types of tasks between the escapes.

1175
00:48:34,630 --> 00:48:36,811
In addition to all the other world variables

1176
00:48:36,811 --> 00:48:38,992
that you have to deal with in a given session.

1177
00:48:38,992 --> 00:48:41,914
The differences also add very deliberate choices

1178
00:48:41,914 --> 00:48:44,115
for the player, so maybe Joan has the piloting skill

1179
00:48:44,115 --> 00:48:46,276
installed from a previous escape,

1180
00:48:46,276 --> 00:48:48,138
but you need to use her for half of the portal

1181
00:48:48,138 --> 00:48:50,759
before sending her off in the shuttle or something.

1182
00:48:50,759 --> 00:48:52,920
Maybe you found some supplies for the crate as Riley,

1183
00:48:52,920 --> 00:48:54,681
but the only way you can use the brain upload escape

1184
00:48:54,681 --> 00:48:55,982
is with her.

1185
00:48:56,369 --> 00:48:58,211
So you have to find somewhere to stash those supplies.

1186
00:48:58,211 --> 00:48:59,932
You know, there are lots of choices, basically,

1187
00:48:59,932 --> 00:49:03,575
the player has to kind of think up or deal with.

1188
00:49:03,575 --> 00:49:05,356
And not only do you have to decide which escape route

1189
00:49:05,356 --> 00:49:06,497
is the most opportune for the character

1190
00:49:06,497 --> 00:49:07,218
you're currently playing,

1191
00:49:07,218 --> 00:49:10,700
but you have to consider characters down the line.

1192
00:49:10,700 --> 00:49:11,921
And again, none of this is prescriptive.

1193
00:49:11,921 --> 00:49:14,403
This is all up to the player to determine the best strategy.

1194
00:49:14,403 --> 00:49:16,765
We don't say you have to do this in this order or whatever.

1195
00:49:16,765 --> 00:49:21,609
So the most elaborate list item is the five-person escape.

1196
00:49:21,609 --> 00:49:24,191
You have to escape in all five different escape routes

1197
00:49:24,191 --> 00:49:25,692
with all five characters in one run.

1198
00:49:26,127 --> 00:49:29,188
without the simulation resetting.

1199
00:49:29,188 --> 00:49:30,969
We wanted to incorporate this

1200
00:49:30,969 --> 00:49:33,890
because it turns the game into this puzzle box, basically,

1201
00:49:33,890 --> 00:49:35,030
where you have to consider things like

1202
00:49:35,030 --> 00:49:36,971
the strengths of the characters,

1203
00:49:36,971 --> 00:49:37,731
the complexity of the escapes,

1204
00:49:37,731 --> 00:49:39,712
and the order that you want to perform them in,

1205
00:49:39,712 --> 00:49:41,352
and the corruption meter because, again,

1206
00:49:41,352 --> 00:49:44,453
the difficulty is ratcheting up over time.

1207
00:49:44,453 --> 00:49:46,734
So then the player has to weigh things like

1208
00:49:46,734 --> 00:49:49,455
should I get an easy escape like the escape pods

1209
00:49:49,455 --> 00:49:50,835
out of the way early or save it for later

1210
00:49:50,835 --> 00:49:52,936
because I'll need an easy win,

1211
00:49:52,936 --> 00:49:54,396
or I could escape with this character right now

1212
00:49:54,396 --> 00:49:55,217
but they could do things.

1213
00:49:55,651 --> 00:49:57,252
in the world to help other characters

1214
00:49:57,252 --> 00:49:58,432
with other escapes down the line.

1215
00:49:58,432 --> 00:50:01,193
Now the speedrunning community has

1216
00:50:01,193 --> 00:50:03,134
eliminated the optimal path by this point,

1217
00:50:03,134 --> 00:50:06,915
but for regular players, for regular human beings,

1218
00:50:06,915 --> 00:50:12,437
there are a lot of interesting variables to sort out,

1219
00:50:12,437 --> 00:50:13,637
in combination with actually playing

1220
00:50:13,637 --> 00:50:14,918
the moment-to-moment game.

1221
00:50:14,918 --> 00:50:18,059
So you've got the planning phase and the execution,

1222
00:50:18,059 --> 00:50:20,020
strategy and tactics kind of playing with each other there.

1223
00:50:27,086 --> 00:50:29,368
All right, so in conclusion,

1224
00:50:29,368 --> 00:50:30,729
so in retooling Prey to make Mooncrash,

1225
00:50:30,729 --> 00:50:34,933
we were looking for what might be next for immersive sims.

1226
00:50:34,933 --> 00:50:36,855
Originally I wanted to have immersive simulations

1227
00:50:36,855 --> 00:50:38,056
are dead or something dramatic here,

1228
00:50:38,056 --> 00:50:39,117
but I don't think that's the case,

1229
00:50:39,117 --> 00:50:40,859
and it's kind of hyperbolic anyway.

1230
00:50:40,859 --> 00:50:42,160
Immersive sims are not dead.

1231
00:50:42,160 --> 00:50:44,983
I think the monolithic vent crawler we're all familiar with

1232
00:50:44,983 --> 00:50:47,725
is no longer the only expression of immersive simulation.

1233
00:50:48,338 --> 00:50:50,859
I think the regimented model is dead,

1234
00:50:50,859 --> 00:50:53,280
and in its wake are all these really amazing possibilities.

1235
00:50:53,280 --> 00:50:56,002
You've got things like a lot of indie projects

1236
00:50:56,002 --> 00:50:57,102
experimenting with the form,

1237
00:50:57,102 --> 00:51:00,644
and adding their own systemic wrinkles to the mix.

1238
00:51:00,644 --> 00:51:02,445
A lot of mainstream games are also adapting

1239
00:51:02,445 --> 00:51:05,367
more and more of the simulation-driven elements

1240
00:51:05,367 --> 00:51:06,527
into their mechanics suites.

1241
00:51:06,527 --> 00:51:08,629
Our big takeaway from this project

1242
00:51:08,629 --> 00:51:11,390
was that you should be willing to break from tradition

1243
00:51:11,390 --> 00:51:12,891
if you're given the opportunity.

1244
00:51:12,891 --> 00:51:15,512
DLC is a really great, fertile ground for that.

1245
00:51:17,826 --> 00:51:19,748
And even if you're not happy with the results,

1246
00:51:19,748 --> 00:51:21,269
and your studio's still open,

1247
00:51:21,269 --> 00:51:23,070
you can always bring some of those lessons

1248
00:51:23,070 --> 00:51:25,192
back to your core projects the next time around.

1249
00:51:25,192 --> 00:51:27,975
Also, don't be timid looking at other genres

1250
00:51:27,975 --> 00:51:29,356
for inspiration.

1251
00:51:29,356 --> 00:51:31,097
We didn't quite go as wide as cart racing

1252
00:51:31,097 --> 00:51:32,458
or collectible card games or something,

1253
00:51:32,458 --> 00:51:34,240
but there were enough different elements

1254
00:51:34,240 --> 00:51:37,182
and problems and roguelikes that resulted

1255
00:51:37,182 --> 00:51:39,104
in this really unorthodox kind of hybrid

1256
00:51:39,104 --> 00:51:41,166
at the end of the day.

1257
00:51:41,166 --> 00:51:42,547
It was one of the most engaging projects

1258
00:51:42,547 --> 00:51:44,448
I think I've worked on, and I don't,

1259
00:51:44,738 --> 00:51:46,580
I think at the end of the day that Mooncrash

1260
00:51:46,580 --> 00:51:47,862
is the future of immersive sims,

1261
00:51:47,862 --> 00:51:51,806
but I think it is a future of immersive sims.

1262
00:51:51,806 --> 00:51:54,869
Special thanks to everyone on this big list.

1263
00:51:54,869 --> 00:51:56,951
I didn't come up with all these cool design ideas.

1264
00:51:56,951 --> 00:51:59,433
There was a design team that we collaborated with

1265
00:51:59,433 --> 00:52:02,437
at Arkane that came up with a lot of cool ideas.

1266
00:52:02,437 --> 00:52:04,018
Special thanks to Clint for mentoring me

1267
00:52:04,018 --> 00:52:07,482
and everyone that sat through my talk.

1268
00:52:07,482 --> 00:52:08,523
And yeah, any questions?

1269
00:52:13,145 --> 00:52:14,306
I think there are two microphones.

1270
00:52:14,306 --> 00:52:14,547
Hi there.

1271
00:52:14,547 --> 00:52:21,493
I think I noticed you said one run takes about one to two hours.

1272
00:52:21,493 --> 00:52:28,740
Does that mean completing five runs in that kind of simulator,

1273
00:52:28,740 --> 00:52:32,783
for each character to each escape is about five to ten hours?

1274
00:52:32,783 --> 00:52:36,327
All total, I think the game ends up,

1275
00:52:36,327 --> 00:52:39,490
I think it ended up longer than Prey.

1276
00:52:40,072 --> 00:52:42,413
Honestly, any given run can take an hour or two,

1277
00:52:42,413 --> 00:52:43,193
a couple of hours.

1278
00:52:43,193 --> 00:52:46,094
And also, that was like the branchy thing

1279
00:52:46,094 --> 00:52:48,375
was kind of a simplified example.

1280
00:52:48,375 --> 00:52:49,976
So I think there were probably like 15 to 21

1281
00:52:49,976 --> 00:52:53,498
to two hour runs in the game, something like that.

